117,130,78,77,81,373,422,411,450,450,433,506,520,535]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3.
Nc3 (3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 {The Fianchetto system has a very solid reputation
against both the Grunfeld and the King's Indian Defenses.} O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3
Nc6 7. O-O e5 8. d5 {This was also Carlsen choice when playing against the
World in 2010.} Ne7 9. e4 b6 ({Both:} 9... a5 10. Ne1 Nd7 11. Nd3 b6 12. Be3
Nc5 13. Nxc5 bxc5 14. Qd2 c6 15. Rac1 cxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Be6 {
Mikhalevski,V (2578)-Zhou,J (2606) Sturbridge 2019}) ({And:} 9... Nd7 {may
transpose into similar positions.}) 10. Rb1 a5 {[#]} 11. Re1 $146 {A solid,
prophylactic move, a'la Petrosian.} ({In is curious that the predecessor was
a game of the future world champion himself, but he chose instead the
straightforward queenside expansion:} 11. a3 Bd7 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 Qc8 14.
c5 bxc5 15. bxc5 Bh3 16. c6 h6 17. Rb7 Ne8 18. Nd2 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 f5 {Petrosian,
T-Panov,V Moscow 1950}) 11... Nd7 12. a3 {Yes, this will be played sooner or
later.} h6 ({Not yet:} 12... f5 13. Ng5) 13. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Gh4] Ding's beloved
manoeuvre, which was invented by the prominent GM Mark Taimanov. It is pure
prophylaxis- Wihte wants to tame the kingside pawns of the opponent and is
ready to put pressure against the f5 pawn whenever it is advanced.} f5 14. exf5
gxf5 15. Qc2 {[%csl Ye5,Yf5] Following the idea. The f5 pawn is under pressure
and none of the duo is risking to make a step further. Notice too that the
advance of the black h-pawn weakened the g6 square and Black can no longer use
it for his knight.} Nf6 ({If:} 15... e4 16. f3 {[%csl Re4,Rf5] destroys the
pair at once.}) (15... f4 {[%csl Re4,Re6,Re8,Rf5,Rf7,Rg4,Rg6,Rg8,Rh5,Rh7]}) 16.
b4 {The kingside is blocked, White resumes his queenside assault.} Bd7 17. c5
axb4 18. axb4 e4 {Carlsen risks, but now the game is opened in his opponent's
favour.} ({In the line:} 18... bxc5 19. bxc5 dxc5 $2 ({But maybe Black can
defend patiently with:} 19... Bc8 $5) ({Or:} 19... Ra5 20. c6 Bc8 21. Rb8 {
True, Black's position is not great in neither cases.}) 20. Rxe5 {Black cannot
successfully trap the rook:} Ne4 {As the compensation that White would get
after either:} 21. Nxe4 ({Or:} 21. Bf4 $5) 21... Bxe5 22. Nxc5 {would be
exuberant.}) 19. c6 Be8 20. f3 $1 {[%csl Rd8,Re8,Yf5,Rf8,Rg8] Of course! Black
is not prepared for the opening of the game.} Nfxd5 ({White's advantage is
indisputable after both:} 20... exf3 21. Bxf3 {[%csl Rf5]}) ({Or:} 20... f4 21.
fxe4 fxg3 22. hxg3 {when there is not enough compensation for a pawn.}) 21.
Nxd5 Nxd5 22. fxe4 ({Black would have surely loved to see:} 22. Qc4 Bf7 23.
Nxf5 Ne3 24. Qxe4 Nxf5 25. Qxf5 Ba2) 22... fxe4 23. Bxe4 {The only little slip
of the Chinese GM in the game.} ({The surprising:} 23. Rxe4 $1 {would have won
as in the line:} Nc3 ({If:} 23... Nf6 24. Rf4 {and Black can hardly move
anything.}) 24. Rg4 {White includes the rook into the attack with decisive
effect, e.g:} Nxb1 25. Bxh6 Rf7 26. Bd5 {[%csl Rg8] and wins.}) 23... Nc3 {
A step in the wrong direction.} ({It was mandatory to give a check once:} 23...
Bd4+ $1 {Then if the king steps on the second rank:} 24. Kg2 ({Also:} 24. Kh1
Nc3 25. Bxh6 Rf2 26. Qd3 Qf6 {allows a chance to Black to defend.}) 24... Nc3 {
The idea that Ding used in the game:} 25. Bxh6 ({Therefore:} 25. Bf3 $1 {
is needed, when Black needs to avoid the greedy:} Nxb1 $2 ({But choose instead:
} 25... Rxf3 $1 26. Nxf3 Bxc6 {when it is unclear.}) 26. Qc4+ {with an instant
win.}) {No longer works due to the obvious:} 25... Rf2+) 24. Bxh6 $1 Qf6 {
Now Carlsen loses by force.} ({It was not too late for:} 24... Bd4+ 25. Be3 {
And now not:} Bxe3+ $2 ({But rather the cementing:} 25... Qf6 $1 26. Rbc1 Ra2
27. Bd5+ Nxd5 28. Qxa2 Bf7 29. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 30. Qf2 Qxf2+ 31. Kxf2 Nxb4 {with
chances for survival.}) 26. Rxe3 Nxb1 27. Bd5+ Kh8 28. Re6 {which is a mating
attack for White.}) 25. Bh7+ Kh8 26. Rxe8 $1 {Removing the key defender of the
light squares when White does whatever he wants.} Rfxe8 ({Perhaps Black should
have at tried:} 26... Bxh6 $1 {Although the study-like:} 27. Re7 $1 {Should
win for White too, in the possible endgame:} Bg7 28. Rbe1 Qd4+ 29. Kh1 Qd5+ 30.
Be4 Nxe4 31. Qxe4 Qxe4+ 32. R1xe4) 27. Ng6+ Kxh7 28. Nf8+ Kxh6 {That leads to
a nice mate.} ({However White was winning anyway:} 28... Kg8 29. Qh7+ Kxf8 (
29... Kf7 30. Rf1) 30. Bxg7+ Qxg7 31. Rf1+) 29. Qh7+ Kg5 30. Qh4+ Kf5 31. Qf4#
{A model game by Ding! 1-0 (31) Ding,L (2836)-Carlsen,M (2881) Magnus Carlsen
Chess Tour Finals benefi 2020 [Bojkov,Dejan]}) 3... Bg7 4. e4 O-O 5. Nf3 d6 6.
Be2 e5 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Re1 c6 9. Bf1 Re8 10. d5 c5 {After blocking the
queenside Geller intends to shift back on his theritory- the king's flank.} 11.
g3 {[%cal Gf3h4,Yf1h3] Taimanov is however preparing a warm welcome for the
f7-f5 advance.} Nf8 (11... Rf8 $5 {[%cal Gf7f5] made more sense. The rook does
not belong to e8 in these positions.}) 12. a3 Ng4 13. Nh4 a6 ({Taimanov's idea
is revealed in the line:} 13... f5 14. exf5 gxf5 15. Bh3 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal
Rh4f5] The pressure against the f5 pawn is sizeable. Black needs to defend the
pawn with:} Qf6 (15... Bf6 16. Nxf5 $1) {Then:} 16. Bxg4 fxg4 17. Ne4 {[%csl
Ge4] Fixes White's advantage in the center, which means that he may look for a
kingside attack himself:} Qe7 18. h3 $1 gxh3 19. Qh5 $16 {[%csl Rg8][%cal
Gc1g5,Gg5h6]}) ({The knight cannot be bothered easily neither:} 13... Bf6 {
Due to:} 14. f3 $1 Bxh4 15. gxh4 Nf6 16. Bg5 Kg7 17. Qd2 $16 {[%csl Rf6,Rf8,
Rg7,Rh6,Rh8][%cal Rg5h6,Rg5f6] Bronstein.}) 14. Bd2 h5 15. h3 Nf6 16. b4 b6 17.
bxc5 bxc5 18. Rb1 N6d7 19. Qa4 $16 Bf6 20. Nf3 h4 21. Nd1 hxg3 22. fxg3 Nb8 23.
Re3 Nh7 24. Reb3 Bd7 25. Qa5 Qc8 26. Nf2 Bd8 27. Qc3 Ba4 28. R3b2 Nd7 29. h4
Ra7 30. Bh3 Qc7 31. Ng5 Nxg5 32. Bxg5 Bxg5 33. hxg5 Kg7 34. Qf3 Qd8 35. Rb7
Rxb7 36. Rxb7 Kg8 37. Bxd7 Bxd7 38. Ng4 Qxg5 39. Rxd7 f5 40. exf5 Rb8 1-0

