{[%evp 0,97,19,31,14,1,47,25,25,25,37,34,73,56,59,25,37,9,20,10,24,31,29,13,26,
17,41,41,44,32,66,53,78,-17,5,22,16,12,30,-28,44,-12,-12,-32,-28,-43,-23,-25,0,
-31,-38,-31,-18,-28,4,4,53,30,35,39,37,48,148,138,138,145,213,213,345,346,413,
189,190,196,551,574,623,635,670,387,359,321,321,449,479,524,524,522,522,522,
530,569,607,601,648,643,910,1424,1603,1812]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6 (2... g6 3. Nc3
Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 {A more modern approach against the Fianchettoe
system runs:} Nc6 7. O-O Bf5 8. d5 Na5 9. Nd2 c5 10. e4 Bd7 11. Qc2 e5 {
Black wants to slow down the opponent's aggression in the center and to gain
back the initiative there. After:} 12. b3 Ng4 {Black obviously wants to play
f7-f5. Then:} 13. Bb2 {[#] Signals that thefirst player is not afraid of the
possible advance. As Botvinnik's idea works well in that case too:} f5 14. exf5
gxf5 15. h3 Nf6 16. f4 $146 {[%csl Ye5,Gf4,Yf5] Curiously enough, this was a
novelty back in 2012!} ({The other normal moves are:} 16. Ne2) ({And:} 16. Rae1
Rb8 17. Nd1 b5) 16... e4 ({The endgame after:} 16... exf4 17. gxf4 ({On the
top of that White may also choose the ultra-aggressive approach:} 17. Ne2 $5
fxg3 18. Nf4 {[%csl Ya5,Rg8][%cal Gf1f3,Gf3g3,Gc2c3] with kingside attack.} Ne8
19. Bxg7 Nxg7 20. Rf3 Qf6 21. Raf1 Kh8 22. Rxg3) 17... Nh5 18. Ne2 ({White is
slightly better as well after the swap of the enemy dark-squared bishop:} 18.
Rae1 Qf6 19. Nd1 Qg6 20. Bxg7 Qxg7 21. Qc3 $14 {As the f5 pawn both limits the
remaining bishop and is a liability itself.}) 18... Bxb2 19. Qxb2 Qf6 20. Qxf6
Nxf6 21. Bf3 ({Perhaps it is even better to put pressure on the weakness at
once with:} 21. Ng3 {[%csl Ra5,Rd7,Rf5][%cal Rd7f5]} b5 22. cxb5 Bxb5 23. Rfe1
Bd7 24. Nf3 h6 25. Nh4 $16 {[%csl Rf5]}) 21... Kf7 22. Kf2 $14 {[%csl Ra5,Rd7,
Rf5][%cal Rd7f5] is pleasant for White due to the bad minor pieces for Black.})
17. Nd1 $1 {An excellent manoeuvre. The knight is perfect on the e3 square from
where it both blocks the e4 pawn, puts pressure on the f5 square and prepares
the g2-g4 advance.} Qe8 ({Best chance for Black seems to be:} 17... Qe7 $5 {
[%csl Gg7][%cal Ge7g7]} 18. Ne3 Nh5 19. Kh2 b5 {although White's play is
definitely easier here. Notice that Black is happy to control the d4 square,
an important factor in these positions.}) {In the following game Wojtaszek
more or less copied Botvinnik's play:} 18. Kh2 ({However, more natural seems:
} 18. Ne3 {[%csl Ge3] Then in case of:} Qg6 ({If:} 18... h5 $5 19. g4 $5 {
seems strong since Black's pieces are unprapared for the opening of the play:}
hxg4 20. hxg4 fxg4 21. f5 {[%csl Rd7,Ye4,Yg4]} Qh5 22. Nxe4 Rae8 23. Rf4 {
[%csl Ya5,Yd7,Rg8]}) ({Black may also try:} 18... Nh5 {But this asks for the
aggressive:} 19. g4 fxg4 ({Or:} 19... Bxb2 20. Qxb2 Ng7 21. Kh2 {[%csl Rg8]
[%cal Gg1g8,Rf1f2,Ga1g1] with attack on the g-file to follow.}) 20. Bxg7 Kxg7
21. Qc3+ {[%csl Ra5,Rg7][%cal Rc3a5,Rc3g7] picking up the knight.}) 19. g4 fxg4
20. hxg4 ({Even better would have been:} 20. f5 $1 Qg5 21. Nxg4 Nxg4 22. hxg4
Qxg4 ({Black is also losing after:} 22... Bxb2 23. Qxb2 Qxg4 24. Nxe4 {[%csl
Rf6][%cal Re4f6]}) 23. f6 Bh6 24. Qc3 Rf7 25. Nxe4 $18 {[%csl Ra5,Rd6][%cal
Gf1f3,Gf3g3,Re4d6,Rc3a5]}) 20... Rae8 $2 ({Black needed to try:} 20... Nxg4 21.
Nxg4 {When White's advantage is minimal after both:} Bxg4 ({Or:} 21... Bxb2 22.
Qxb2 Bxg4 23. Nxe4 $14) 22. Nxe4 $14 (22. Bxg7 Qxg7 23. Nxe4) 22... Bf5 $140
23. Bxg7 Qxg7 24. Qc3 Qxc3 25. Nxc3 a6 26. Rae1 Rae8 27. Kh2 {[%csl Ya5]}) 21.
f5 Qg5 22. Rae1 Qh4 ({Here:} 22... Nxg4 {loses to:} 23. Nxg4 Bxb2 24. Qxb2 Qxg4
25. Nxe4 $18 {[%csl Rd6,Gf6,Rg4,Rg8][%cal Ge4f6,Re4d6,Gf1f3,Gf3g3]}) 23. Nxe4
Nxe4 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. Bxe4 {[%csl Ra5,Rg7][%cal Rc2c3,Rc3a5,Rc3g7] The knight
on a5 remains vulnerable, but above all- too far away from the kingside. Black
is doomed:} Re5 26. Bf3 h5 27. Ng2 $18 {[%csl Ge6,Gh5][%cal Gg2f4,Gf4e6,Gf4h5]}
Qg3 28. Qd2 hxg4 29. Qg5+ Kh8 30. Qh6+ Kg8 31. Qg6+ {1-0 Black resigns. 1-0 
(31) Baryshpolets,A (2487)-Turov,M (2667) Voronezh 2020}) 18... Qg6 19. Rf2 {
[%csl Rg4][%cal Gd1e3,Ga1g1,Gf2g2,Gg3g4] Wojtaszek prepares the kingside play
similarly to Botvinnik.} Kf7 {A poor move.} ({More resilient seems:} 19... Nh5
$5 20. Nf1 Rf7 ({But not:} 20... Bd4 $4 21. Bxd4 cxd4 22. b4 {[%csl Ra5] a
line, which reveals another problem for the second player- his poor knight.})
21. Qd2 $14) 20. Ne3 Rg8 21. Rg1 Bh6 22. Bh1 b6 {Now that everything is ready:}
23. g4 $1 {[%csl Yf5,Rf7,Yg6] Opens the game in favor of White.} fxg4 ({After:
} 23... Nh5 {White has a pleasant choice between:} 24. Nxf5 $1 ({And:} 24. g5
$16) 24... Bxf5 25. Bxe4 Bxf4+ 26. Kh1 Bxe4+ 27. Nxe4 Rae8 28. Nxd6+ $1 {
With decisive attack after:} Qxd6 29. Qxh7+ Ng7 30. Rgf1 Ke7 31. Bxg7 Kd8 32.
Rxf4 $18) 24. Rg3 $1 {[%csl Re4,Gg3] Plugs-in the holes on the kingside. With
the fall of the e4 pawn, Black's positon collapses.} Rae8 ({Or:} 24... Qh5 25.
Nxe4 ({White also wins with the help of:} 25. Bxf6 Kxf6 26. Nxe4+ Ke7 27. f5
Bxe3 28. Rxe3 Qh6 29. f6+ Kd8 30. Qc3 $18) 25... Nxe4 26. Bxe4 $18 {with
winning attack.}) 25. Bxf6 Qxf6 26. Nxe4 Qe7 27. Nxg4 {The simplest.} ({
White is won as well with:} 27. Ng5+ Kf8 ({Or:} 27... Bxg5 28. Qxh7+ Rg7 29.
fxg5+ $18 {[%csl Rf7]}) 28. Nf5 $18) 27... Bxg4 28. hxg4 Qh4+ 29. Rh3 Qxg4 30.
Ng5+ Bxg5 31. Qxh7+ {1-0 Black resigns. 1-0 (31) Wojtaszek,R (2704)-Fedorov,A 
(2609) Cesko 2020 [Velickovic,Sa, Bojkov, D]}) 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g3 g6
6. Bg2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 Re8 9. d5 Nc5 10. Ne1 a5 11. h3 Rf8 (11... Nh5 $5
12. Kh2 Bd7 13. Bf3 Nf6 14. Nd3 b6 15. Be3 Rf8 16. Rc1 Qc8 $10) 12. Be3 Ne8 13.
Nd3 b6 14. Qd2 {[#]} f5 15. exf5 gxf5 ({Against:} 15... Bxf5 {Botvinnik
planned:} 16. Nxc5 dxc5 17. g4 $16 {[%csl Re4,Yg7][%cal Gc3e4,Gg2e4]
Establishing firm control over the e4 square and "killing" the fianchettoed
bishop. More about this method in another video.}) 16. f4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc8,
Ye5,Gf4,Yf5][%cal Yc8f5]} Nxd3 $6 {Another inaccuracy.} ({Botvinnik wrote that
Boleslavsky disliked:} 16... e4 17. Nf2 {[%cal Gg3g4] with the positional
threat of g3-g4. But at least then Black could have kept the strong knight on
c5 alive.} ({Weaker is:} 17. Nxc5 dxc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc5d4] As Black takes
under control the important d4 square. More about the importance of that
square in another video.})) 17. Qxd3 e4 18. Qd2 {[%csl Rc8,Ye4][%cal Ga2a3,
Gb2b4,Gc4c5] Botvinnik: "Almost all commentators evaluated this position in
Black's favour, which is wrong. On the queenside White has an indisputable
advantage, as he can advance his pawns with a2-a3, b2-b4 and c4-c5. The
central passer on e4 might be dangerous in a possible pawn endgame, but it
will not happen any time soon. The only White's relative weakness on g3 can be
easily defended." Two more things should be added- the bishop on c8 is
practically smothered, and it is also White who is better on the kingside as
the g3-g4 advance would undermine the e4 pawn and it will be eventually lost
by Black. In this game, Botvinnik did not get a chance to demonstrate the
correct plan which is to positon the dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal,
whereas the white knight would love to occupy the blockading square on e3. But
with some excellent prophylactical moves he won the battle on the kingside.}
Qf6 19. Rf2 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Yd2b2]} Bd7 20. Rd1 {[%csl Rd4]} Qg6 21. Ne2 Nf6
22. Bd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd4h8]} Rae8 23. Qe3 (23. Re1 h5 $1) 23... h6 {
Boleslavsky starts to lose track of the position.} (23... Kf7 $1 {[%cal Gf8g8]
would have been more to the point.}) 24. Nc3 Rf7 25. Bf1 $1 {Excellent
regroupment which prevents Black's initiative on the kingside before it even
started.} Kh7 26. Be2 {[%csl Ge2,Gg4][%cal Gg3g4,Gf2g2]} h5 {In reality this
is a purely defensive set-up.} 27. Rg2 Bh6 28. Rf1 $1 Rg8 29. Rff2 Bg7 30. a3 {
After all the kingside prophylaxis White finally indicates where he will play.}
h4 $2 {Which provokes nervous reaction by his opponent.} 31. gxh4 $1 {[%csl
Rf5][%cal Gg2g8,Rg2g5,Rg5f5] An excellent move.} ({Although:} 31. g4 $1 fxg4
32. hxg4 Nxg4 33. Bxg4 Bxd4 34. Qxd4 Bxg4 35. Nxe4 {might have been even
better when White is close to winning.}) 31... Qh6 32. Rg5 Qxh4 (32... Ne8 $5 {
was the most resilient defence.}) 33. Rfg2 Be8 34. Rxf5 {And Black's position
collapsed after:} Bh6 35. Rfg5 $3 Bxg5 36. fxg5 $18 {[%csl Rh7]} Nh5 37. Bxh5 (
37. Nxe4 {would have been faster.}) 37... Qxh5 38. Qxe4+ Rg6 39. Qxe8 Rxg5 40.
Qh8+ Kg6 41. Qg8+ Kf5 42. Qc8+ Kf4 43. Qe6 Rxg2+ 44. Kxg2 Qf3+ 45. Kg1 Qg3+ 46.
Kf1 Qf3+ 47. Bf2 Qh5 48. Ne2+ Kg5 49. h4+ 1-0

