{[%evp 0,81,19,29,23,-13,35,36,37,33,38,38,30,38,56,27,23,16,41,25,12,16,2,7,
23,-1,26,7,15,8,21,4,19,19,50,34,78,81,77,64,54,3,106,126,157,160,196,201,214,
144,185,222,231,208,244,249,252,221,220,220,240,251,236,195,338,336,341,341,
352,358,362,361,372,375,386,356,368,378,379,379,387,387,425,428]} 1. Nf3 (1. c4
Nf6 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 d5 4. Qc2 e5 5. d3 h6 6. Nf3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 dxe4 9.
dxe4 c5 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Be3 Nd4 12. Bxd4 cxd4 13. Nb5 Bb8 14. Ne1 {[%csl Gd3,
Re5][%cal Ge1d3,Gh2h3,Gf2f4]} Bd7 15. Na3 {The first time Botvinnik applied
his second method was at this point of his game against Kortschnoi. White
wants to undermine the black centre with Ne1-d3 followed by f2-f4. The problem
with the immediate f2-f4, however, is that the black knight will jump on g4 and
then land on e3. Therefore, White also needs to insert the h2-h3 move. This
will however weaken the dark squares. And the dark squares are especially
sensitive since White lacks his dark-squared bishop. Therefore:} h5 $1 {
[%csl Rg3,Rh4][%cal Rh5h4,Rh2h3,Rh4g3] Deep, aggressive prophylaxis!} 16. Nd3 {
[%cal Gh2h3,Gf2f4]} (16. h3 {does not work due to:} h4 $1 {[%csl Rf4,Rg3,Rh4]})
({Neither does:} 16. f4 $2 Ng4 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gg4e3] followed by Ng4-e3.})
16... h4 $1 {Botvinnik attacked the g3 point just in time to prevent the
above-mentioned manoeuvre. However, the positives behind the h-pawn advance do
not end here. Black is successfully opening the king's flank which coupled with
his extra space and strong centre yields him strong attack. After:} 17. c5 Qe7
18. Nc4 hxg3 19. hxg3 Bc7 20. b4 b5 21. Nd2 Bc6 22. Rae1 g6 {[%csl Rg1][%cal
Gg8g7,Gf8h8,Gh8h1,Rf6h7,Rh7g5,Rf7f5] Black intends Kg8-g7, Rf8-h8 and
eventually Nf6-g5 manoeuvre when finally it will be Black to open the centre
with f7-f5. In brief- Botvinnik won with a direct attack.} 23. Nb3 Kg7 24. f4 Ng4
25. fxe5 Rad8 26. Qb2 Nxe5 27. Nf4 Nc4 28. Qf2 Be5 29. Ne2 Qd7 30. Nf4 Qg4 31.
Qf3 Qg5 32. Rf2 Ne3 33. Bh3 Rde8 34. Na5 Bxf4 35. Qxf4 Qxf4 36. gxf4 Bxe4 37.
Rd2 Bf5 38. Bxf5 Nxf5 39. Rxe8 Rxe8 40. Nc6 Re1+ 41. Kf2 Re4 42. Nxa7 Rxf4+ {
1/2-1/2 (42) Kortschnoj, V-Botvinnik, M Moscow 1952}) 1... Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. d5 Na6 $6 {I believe that this move is
dubious. White's idea is that after} ({In the past Black was trying to advance
the f-pawn at once with:} 7... Ne8 {[%cal Gf7f5] But here too, White can apply
Botvinnik's idea:} 8. h4 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Rh4h5]} ({Not:} 8. O-O f5 {[%cal
Ge8f6] when Black gets what he wants.}) 8... f5 ({Black can, of course, stop the
h-pawn advance:} 8... h5 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Rf7f5] But this will also weaken his
kingside, in particular, the g6 pawn and the g5 square. The latter might be
used as an excellent stepping stone for both the kingside attack and the
knight transfer to the e4 square. For example:} 9. Bg5 f6 10. Be3 f5 11. exf5
gxf5 ({Or:} 11... Bxf5 12. Bd3 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf3g5,Gg5e4] followed by
Nf3-g5-e4 with a strong grip on the e4 square.}) 12. Ng5 {[%csl Rg8,Rh5][%cal
Re2h5] and Black loses the h5 pawn.}) 9. h5 f4 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. g3 Nd7 ({
White is perfectly fine with the kingside blockade in case of:} 11... g5 12.
Bd2 g4 13. Nh4 f3 14. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Ge1,Rg4,Rg7,Rg8][%cal Rg7e5,Rc8g4,
Gd1c2,Ge1c1,Gc1b1,Gc4c5] as he is having a clear edge on the queenside and can
further expand there after 0-0-0, Kc1-b1, Rd1-c1 and the c-pawn thrust. Notice
how poor the black bishops are and how helpless he is on his own flank.}) 12.
Bd2 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gd1c2,Ge1c1,Rh1h8,Rh1h2]} Qe7 13. Qc2 Nef6 14. O-O-O $5
$16 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gh1h8] With clear edge for White.} ({Although the
immediate attack of the g-pawn was a plausible option too with either:} 14.
gxf4 $1 exf4 15. Rg1 $1 $16 {[%csl Rg6,Rg8]}) ({Or:} 14. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Rg6]}
Qf7 15. Rg1 $16 {[%csl Rg6,Rg8] when in both cases White is close to winning.})
14... fxg3 15. fxg3 Nc5 16. Nh4 Qe8 17. Rdf1 Ng4 18. b4 Na6 19. a3 Nf2 20. Rh2
Ng4 21. Rxf8+ Bxf8 22. Rh1 Be7 23. Kb2 Bd7 24. Qc1 Qf7 25. Rf1 Qg7 26. c5 Nb8
27. Bg5 Nf6 28. Bc4 Kh7 29. c6 Bc8 30. Rh1 Kg8 31. Qd2 a6 32. Bb3 b5 33. Rf1 a5
34. Qe2 axb4 35. axb4 Na6 36. Qf3 Kf7 37. Na2 Bh3 38. Rf2 Bc8 39. g4 {1-0 (39)
Gligoric, S-Bogdanovic, R Titovo Uzice 1966}) 8. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b4] the
"a6" remains out of play ( White is threatening a2-a3 and b2-b4).} Ne8 {
Black's only idea is to realize the f7-f5 advance as soon as possible. In this
way, Black could play the move Nc5 with a tempo.} ({Very often, when White's
dark-squared bishop is closed by "Nd2", Black has at his disposal the move} 
8... Bh6 {This continuation would have been quite an acceptable option, if
White had already castled short. In the concrete position, however, the rook
on "h1" gives us some additional resources.} 9. h4 {[%csl Rg8,Rh4][%cal Rh4h5]}
Nc5 10. h5 $1 {White's idea is based on this sacrifice.} Bxd2+ (10... Bg5 11.
b4) 11. Qxd2 Ncxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qh6 {[%csl Rg8,Rh7][%cal Rh5g6,Rh6h7]} Qf6
14. Be3 {The attack is very dangerous. You can have a look at the following
variations:} Qe7 (14... Bf5 15. O-O-O Qg7 16. Qxg7+ Kxg7 17. hxg6 Kxg6 18. g4
Bd7 19. Bd3 f5 20. Rdg1 {Once White manage to open the kingside, he has a
crushing attack.}) ({The move} 14... Qg7 {loses by force:} 15. Qxg7+ Kxg7 16.
hxg6 hxg6 17. Bh6+ {[%csl Rf8,Rg7]}) (14... Re8 15. O-O-O Qg7 16. hxg6 hxg6 (
16... fxg6 17. Qh4) 17. Qh4 {[%csl Rg7,Rg8][%cal Gh1h2,Gd1h1,Ge3h6]}) 15. Bd3
Nc5 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. hxg6 fxg6 18. Bxg6 Bf5 19. Bxf5 Rxf5 20. O-O Rd8 21. Rae1
Rd6 22. Qh3 Qg5 23. Rxe5 $1 $18) 9. h4 $1 {[%csl Rg8,Gh5][%cal Gh4h5] Again,
we use this mighty attacking idea.} f5 {Black has no other options.} ({If} 9...
h6 {then} 10. h5 g5 11. g4 {[%csl Gd5,Rd6,Ge4,Re5,Gg4,Rg5,Rg7,Gh5,Rh6][%cal
Gc4c5,Ga2a3,Gb2b4] We are already aware of the fact that in such type of
positions, White is winning.}) 10. h5 gxh5 {White was threatening to open the
"h" file for the rook.} 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Nde4 {As a result of the f7-f5 break,
white has obtained a firm control over the key "e4" square. Moreover, Black's
kingside is completely destroyed.} Nc5 13. Ng3 $1 e4 14. Nxh5 Bg4 {An original
trap, to which we don't pay attention.} (14... Nd3+ 15. Kf1 Bg4 16. Nxe4) 15.
Kf1 $1 (15. Qd2 Bxe2 16. Kxe2 Be5 17. Qg5+ Qxg5 18. Bxg5 {With a considerable
edge in the endgame.}) 15... Bxh5 16. Rxh5 Nf6 17. Rh3 Qe7 18. Be3 Nfd7 19. Qc2
a5 20. g3 $1 {[%csl Re4,Rh7][%cal Gf1g2,Ga1h1] If we manage to regroup our
pieces, Black position is hopeless. The pawns "e4" and "h7" are too weak,
while the king is exposed. White's bishop pair is an important factor too.} Rf6
21. Kg2 Raf8 22. Rah1 h6 23. Rh4 $1 {After this strong move, the game is over
- Black loses at least a pawn. There is no point in commenting for the rest of the
game.} Rf5 24. Bg4 Re5 25. Bxh6 Nf6 26. Be3 Qf7 27. Qe2 Nxg4 28. Qxg4 Qf3+ 29.
Kg1 Qxg4 30. Rxg4 Nd3 31. b3 Rfe8 32. Bd4 e3 33. fxe3 R8e7 34. Bxe5 Nxe5 35.
Re4 Kf7 36. Kg2 Kg6 37. Nb5 Bf6 38. Nd4 c6 39. dxc6 bxc6 40. Nf3 Rb7 41. Rd1
1-0

