{[%evp 0,54,37,34,34,31,33,26,20,34,43,40,45,66,18,53,54,60,59,63,62,67,50,86,
78,72,72,72,101,119,120,127,127,127,140,137,76,81,73,138,161,161,160,199,275,
287,287,280,273,241,160,163,262,264,302,332,353]} {The correct treatment of
the position was demonstrated by the Partriarch more than half a century ago:} 
11... Bxf5 $2 12. g4 $1 {[%csl Re4] Compare with Batchulun's game! The e4
square is consistently cleared for the white pieces.} Bd7 {[%cal Ge5e4]} 13. h3
$1 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gh3g4,Re5e4,Rf3f4] An important move in White's set-up.
Black's only chance is to open the long diagonal for his bishop, but Botvinnik
makes sure that this will not come for free.} a6 (13... e4 {only helps White
after:} 14. f4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ye4,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gh3h4,Gh4h5,Ge1c1,Ge1g1,Re2f1,
Rf1g2] Then White castles long, places his rooks behind the -g and -h pawns
and sweeps the enemy kingside.} (14. fxe4 {[%csl Ge4] is OK as well actually.})
) 14. O-O-O {Here the queenside expansion:} b5 {Is nicely met with:} 15. c5 $1
b4 16. Ne4 {[%csl Ge4,Rg7] When Alexander missed his last chance by playing:}
a5 {He wants to bring his other bishop into life, but White does not object
this idea at all.} ({The last chance to bring the bishop in the game was
related to the Gligoric's Exchange Sacrifice idea:} 16... Nxe4 $1 17. fxe4 Bb5
$14 18. h4 $140 Rf4 $1 {Simple maths will help you understand why this move is
not even a sacrifice. The bishop on g7 is worth about a pawn at this stage of
the game, but once that it gets control of the long diagonal it is definitely
worth more than his usual three pawns!} 19. Bxf4 exf4 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gg7a1]
See David- Firouzja.}) 17. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4] Now the knight can be always
replaced by a bishop on the e4 square. Whichever piece stands there exerts
strong pressure against the opponent's kingside while blocking the
dark-squared black bishop. A nightmare scenario for Black!} Qe7 18. c6 $1 {
[%csl Rd7]} Bc8 {[%csl Ya8,Yc8,Yf8]} 19. h4 Ba6 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. g5 Bg7 22.
Be4 $16 {[%csl Ya6,Ge3,Ge4,Yg7,Rg8][%cal Ya6f1,Gh4h5,Yg7e5] Compare the
bishops and you will know why White is winning effortlessly.} Bc8 23. h5 Bf5
24. hxg6 Bxg6 25. Qd3 {A small combination to grow White's advantage even
further.} Rxf3 26. Bxg6 hxg6 27. Qxg6 Kf8 (27... Rxe3 28. Rdf1 {is mate.}) 28.
Qe4 Qf7 29. g6 $1 {Forces the trades of the last black active pieces.} Qf5 30.
Qxf5+ Rxf5 31. Rdf1 $1 Rxf1+ 32. Rxf1+ Kg8 33. Rf7 {[%csl Ra5,Rc7,Rg7][%cal
Gc1c2,Gc2d3,Gd3e4,Ge4f5,Gf5e6,Gc2b3,Gb3a4,Ga4a5] White's extra king quickly
wraps up the game.} Rc8 34. Kc2 e4 35. b3 Bc3 36. Kd1 Be5 37. Ke2 Bc3 38. Ba7
1-0

