{[%evp 0,68,27,12,87,57,43,33,33,38,45,31,31,24,36,33,43,10,20,20,18,18,9,9,16,
1,9,4,14,-19,41,44,46,19,19,2,-1,25,25,26,28,24,24,8,13,-4,94,28,101,119,124,
133,133,133,133,-31,-26,-64,-19,-109,-109,-113,-129,-131,-126,-193,-153,-153,
-153,-183,-184]} 1. Nf3 g6 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Be2 Nbd7
7. O-O e5 8. d5 Nc5 9. Qc2 ({Another common line is:} 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bxf6 (10.
Bh4 g5 {[%csl Re4]}) 10... Bxf6 11. b4 Nd7 12. Nd2 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc4c5,Gd2c4]}
Bg5 13. Nb3 f5 14. c5 Nf6 15. Bf3 Kg7 16. Re1 h5 {[%cal Rh6c1]} 17. a4 Bf4 18.
Ra2 {[%cal Ga2c2]} fxe4 19. Nxe4 Bf5 20. Na5 Nxe4 21. Bxe4 Bxh2+ 22. Kxh2 Qh4+
23. Kg1 Bxe4 24. cxd6 cxd6 25. Nxb7 Rf6 26. f3 Bxd5 {[%csl Ra2,Rb7,Re1][%cal
Rh4e1]}) (9. Nd2 {[%csl Re4]} a5) 9... a5 10. Bg5 h6 11. Be3 Nfd7 12. Nd2 f5
13. exf5 gxf5 14. f4 exf4 $1 {Active piece play against the static centre is
one of Black's best ideas. After:} (14... e4 {[%csl Gc3,Rc8,Gd2,Ge2,Ge3,Re4,
Rf5][%cal Gg1h1,Gf1g1,Gg2g4] White's play is easier as witnessed before. His
plan is to ultimately prepare and execute g2-g4 to undermine the black strong
centre.}) 15. Bxf4 Ne5 {In return for slightly the compromised pawn structure
Black brought his pieces into life. The squares e4, g4, the long diagonal and
the play along the g-file fully compensate him.} 16. Nf3 Bd7 17. Rae1 Qf6 {
[%csl Rf5,Rh6][%cal Gf6a1,Gf6g6,Ge5g4,Gg4e3,Ga8e8] Black compensates for the
kingside weaknesses thanks to his superb pieces.} ({A classical example of the
development for both sides is the following game:} 17... Qe7 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19.
Be3 b6 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5]} 20. Kh1 Kh8 21. Qd2 Qd6 22. Bd1 {[%cal Gd1c2,Ge1e5,
Gf1f5]} Rf7 23. Bc2 Qf8 24. Ne2 Nb7 {[%cal Ga8e8,Gb7d6] Plasket-Nunn}) 18. Nxe5
{White cannot stand the strong enemy knight. That is a common way to fight
the opponent's initiative. The hanging pawns might be turned into targets as
the white rooks already stand comfortably eyeing them.} dxe5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5]
[%cal Gf5f4,Ge5e4] However now Black has two mobile hanging pawns. This pawn
structure is unstable but provides a lot of counter-chances to the second
player in the middlegame.} 19. Be3 b6 $11 ({Weaker seems:} 19... Qd6 {as after:
} 20. Nb5 $1 {The black queen has to self-pin:} Qb6 (20... Bxb5 21. cxb5 Ne4
22. Bd3 {with advantage for White.}) 21. a3 $6 (21. Kh1 $14) 21... a4 22. Kh1
f4 23. Bg1 e4 {Still, after a serious inaccuracy:} 24. Bh5 $2 e3 $15 {Black
eventually managed to prove the power of the hanging duo.} 25. Bg6 Nb3 26. g3
Bxb5 27. cxb5 fxg3 28. Rxf8+ Rxf8 29. Rxe3 gxh2 30. Bf7+ Kh8 31. Qxh2 Qf6 32.
Be6 Nd4 33. Qxc7 Nf3 34. Bf2 Ne5 35. Rg3 Qh4+ 36. Kg1 Qf6 37. Qxg7+ Qxg7 38.
Rxg7 Kxg7 39. Bd4 Kf6 40. Kg2 Re8 41. Bd7 Rg8+ 42. Kf1 Rd8 43. Be6 Rd6 44. Bg8
Kf5 45. Bc5 Rd8 46. Be6+ Ke4 47. Be7 Rxd5 48. Bxd5+ Kxd5 49. Ke2 Kc4 50. Bf6
Ng4 51. Bg7 Kxb5 52. Kf3 h5 53. Kf4 Kc4 54. Kg5 Nf2 55. Kxh5 Kb3 56. Kg5 Nd3
57. Kf5 Nxb2 58. Bf8 Nc4 59. Ke4 Nxa3 60. Kd5 b5 {0-1 (60) Czebe,A (2350)
-Sutovsky,E (2410) Budapest 1993}) 20. Kh1 Qg6 21. Rf2 Bf6 22. Rf3 Qh7 (22...
Qg7 $1 {would have been stronger as Black does not need to worry about:} 23.
Rg3 Bg5 24. h4 $2 f4) 23. Qd2 Bg7 24. d6 c6 25. Bxc5 ({Now it is White's term
to miss a strong resource:} 25. Rh3 $1 $16 f4 $140 26. Bxc5 bxc5 27. Bd3) 25...
bxc5 26. Na4 e4 27. Rg3 $2 f4 28. Bg4 fxg3 29. Bxd7 Bd4 30. Bxc6 e3 31. Qd1
Rad8 32. Qg4+ Qg7 33. Qe6+ Kh8 34. hxg3 Qf6 0-1

