{[%evp 0,47,29,-2,31,31,31,31,31,31,31,31,36,32,53,38,49,16,33,13,58,68,77,84,
83,90,64,58,51,63,50,-26,-28,-31,-51,-30,-19,-3,-9,-17,-17,-16,-11,-21,-21,-15,
-3,0,1,1]} 1. c4 g6 2. Nc3 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. d4 Nf6 5. e4 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O
Nbd7 8. Re1 c6 9. d5 c5 10. a3 Ne8 11. Bg5 f6 12. Bd2 f5 13. Ng5 Nc7 14. exf5
gxf5 15. f4 e4 16. Be3 h6 17. Nh3 {[%cal Gh3f2,Gf2e4,Rg2g4,Gb2b4]} Bxc3 $3 {
Brilliant strategical decision! In return for his pride and honor Black
receives the following: 1) The knight is no longer a threat for the f5+e4 pair
and neither attacks the e4 pawn nor will it ever maneuver to the e3 square. 2)
The b2-b4 advance is no longer an issue neither. 3) The pawn on c3 together
with the pawn on f4, as well as the black's one on c5 lock the enemy bishop in
a cage.} 18. bxc3 {[%csl Rc3,Gd4,Re3,Rf4][%cal Re3f4,Re3d4,Rc5d4]} Nf6 19. a4
Kh8 $1 {[%cal Gf8g8]} 20. Nf2 {Still hoping to advance the g-pawn but in vain.}
Rg8 21. Kh1 Qe8 22. Rg1 Qg6 23. Qd2 Bd7 24. g3 Rae8 $1 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Ga1b1,
Gd7c8,Gc8b7] The black bishop can defend the queenside on its own.} 25. a5 Re7
26. Rab1 Bc8 27. Rg2 Reg7 28. Rbg1 Nce8 29. h3 h5 1/2-1/2

