{[%evp 0,74,24,26,18,4,31,31,29,45,45,27,25,9,26,17,17,-10,-9,-20,-17,-28,-34,
-10,2,-3,21,21,35,35,66,40,65,38,16,71,39,26,25,52,51,54,32,41,23,7,45,45,34,
28,48,-20,-19,-28,-31,-36,-26,-97,-99,-155,-181,-188,-132,-122,-79,-201,-79,
-120,0,-200,-213,-216,-200,-350,-394,-842,-602]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3 {A look in the base reveals that Radjabov hade
never faced this move before. While Vallejo had never even developed the light-squared bishop on e2 on the previous move.} ({In the Averbakh System White
often tries to lure the pawn on h6 before stepping gon e3 with} 6. Bg5 h6 7. Be3
) 6... e5 7. d5 a5 8. g4 Na6 9. h4 {Not really an attack, but more of defensive prophylaxis. White wants to clamp the kingside.} Nc5 10. f3 h5 11. g5
Nh7 ({Very often this knight is rerouted to the queenside with} 11... Nfd7 12.
Nh3 Nb6 {as in Debashis,D (2472)-Firouzja,A (2456) Doha 2016}) 12. Kd2 $146 {
A novelty. The king is often safe behind the blocked centre in these lines.} ({
The "normal" way to play it is} 12. Qd2 f6 13. gxf6 ({Or} 13. O-O-O fxg5 14.
hxg5 Bd7 15. Nh3 Qe7 16. Kb1 Rf7 17. Nf2 Raf8 18. Rdg1 Rf4 {1/2-1/2 (18)
Riazantsev,A (2646)-Amonatov,F (2592) St Petersburg 2015}) {In a recent game
from the ETCC White was better after} 13... Rxf6 ({However} 13... Bxf6 {
seems more natural to play.}) 14. O-O-O Bd7 15. Nh3 {Rodshtein,M (2699)
-Kovalev,V (2636) Heraklio 2017}) ({Another option for White is} 12. Nh3 {
For example} Bxh3 {I do not like this...} 13. Rxh3 f6 14. gxf6 (14. Qd2 $5)
14... Rxf6 15. Qd2 {which looks good for White, Debashis, D (2472) -Karthikeyan,
M (2578) Moscow 2017}) 12... Bd7 {Radjabov proceeds with the normal
development and prepares the opening of the centre.} 13. Nh3 c6 14. Nf2 cxd5
15. exd5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc3e4,Gf2e4] Vallejo's point. His knights get an
access to the wonderful e4 spot.} ({Or} 15. cxd5 a4 {followed by Qd8-a5 and
b7-b5 with strong play on the queenside.}) 15... f5 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4][%cal Ge5e4,
Gf5f4]} ({The computer recommends} 15... b6 {but no real KID player will allow}
16. Nfe4 {that easily.}) 16. gxf6 Nxf6 17. Bxc5 $6 {A contraversial decision.
The knights will make it to the e4 square, but the bishop on g7 remains
without an opponent.} (17. Nfe4 Ncxe4+ 18. Nxe4 Nxe4+ 19. fxe4 Rf4 $1 {[%csl
Rb2][%cal Rg7b2]} 20. Bxf4 exf4 {[%csl Rb2,Rd2,Rd4,Gg7][%cal Gd8b6,Gg7b2,Rb6d4,
Rb6b2,Rd4e3]}) 17... dxc5 18. Kc2 ({Some of the problems due to the lack of
the white bishop are revealed in the line} 18. Nfe4 {[%csl Ge4]} Nxe4+ 19. Nxe4
Rf4 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Rf4h4] The pawn on h4 became vulnerable.} 20. Qe1 Qb6 {
[%csl Rb2]} 21. Kc2 Bf5 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Rf5c2] and Black is better.}) 18... a4
(18... e4 $5 {[%cal Rg7a1] was already interesting, but before breaking
through Radjabov wants to soften the long diagonal.}) 19. Qd2 a3 {[%csl Rb2]}
20. b3 e4 $1 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gg7a1] Every KID players knows ;) This idea,
reminiscent of the glorious game Kotov-Gligoric from the Interzonal tournament
in Zurich 1953 is the main weapon of every KID player. The Beast on g7 is
released and things do not look rosy for Vallejo at all. To make things worse,
he was getting very low on time.} 21. fxe4 ({Worse was} 21. Nfxe4 Nxe4 22. fxe4
Rf2 {[%cal Gf2a2,Gg7a1] and Black breaks into the opponent's camp.}) 21... Ng4
22. Nxg4 (22. Nd3 {is too artificial to be true. After} Bh6 23. Qe1 Ne3+ 24. Kb1
Qe7 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gh6c1,Ge7e5,Ge7h4] Black develops strong attack on the
dark squares.}) 22... hxg4 {I could not believe my eyes when I saw the
computer evaluation here (0.00)... Black's play is very easy and strong. Queen
will come out on either f6 or e7 than on the long diagonal, rooks want to get
into the second file, there a strong passer on g3...} ({Of course not} 22...
Bxg4 23. Bxg4 hxg4 {which will make White's defence easier.}) 23. h5 ({Or} 23.
Raf1 Rxf1 24. Bxf1 Qf6 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7][%cal Rf6a1,Ra8f8] and the black pieces
dominate the board.}) 23... Rf2 24. h6 ({In case of} 24. hxg6 {Black will
simply ignore the g6 pawn and proceed with his plan-} Qe7 25. Rh7 ({Even the
endgame is bad for White after} 25. d6 Qe5 26. Qd5+ Qxd5 27. cxd5 g3 $1 ({
No need to complicate thing with} 27... Bxc3 {when a curious line that leads
to a draw runs after} 28. Kxc3 Rxe2 29. Rh7 Be8 30. Rah1 g3 31. d7 g2 32. Rh8+
Kg7 33. R1h7+ Kxg6 34. Rh6+ Kg5 35. Rh5+ Bxh5 36. Rxa8 Re3+ 37. Kd2 Re2+))
25... g3 {with big advantage for the second player.}) 24... Be5 25. Raf1 g3 {
[%cal Gg4g3,Ge5c3,Gf2a2]} 26. Rxf2 ({Or} 26. Qe3 Rh2 $1 (26... Qf6 27. Nd1 Rxf1
28. Rxf1 Qe7 {looks less convincing.})) 26... gxf2 27. Nd1 Qf6 28. Rf1 Bd4 29.
Nxf2 {Vallejo understands that the position is hopeless strategically and tries
tactics. But this only speeds up his defeat.} (29. Bd3 Rf8 30. h7+ Kxh7 31.
Rh1+ Kg8 32. Qh6 Rf7 {leads White nowhere neither.}) 29... Bxf2 30. e5 Qxe5
31. Rxf2 Bf5+ 32. Kd1 (32. Rxf5 Qxf5+ {is hopeless as well.}) 32... Qa1+ {
Not the only wy to win the game, but convincing enough.} 33. Qc1 Qxa2 34. Rxf5
Qxb3+ ({Surely} 34... gxf5 $4 {would give the win to White after} 35. Qg5+ Kf7
36. Qg7+ Ke8 37. h7) 35. Kd2 Qa2+ {Radjabov repeats the moves once.} (35... a2
{would have won after} 36. Qa1 Qb4+ 37. Kc2 Qb1+ 38. Qxb1 axb1=Q+ 39. Kxb1 gxf5
) 36. Ke1 {Vallejo deviates, but there is no salvation anyways.} (36. Kd1 Qb3+
{would force Radjabov to use the winning line from above.}) 36... Qb2 37. Qf4
Qb1+ 0-1

