{[%evp 0,102,19,31,25,-16,57,30,33,37,44,55,58,32,27,31,64,18,13,18,18,12,13,
14,16,3,45,47,45,14,18,5,67,6,20,17,24,25,17,-10,-12,-33,-39,-13,0,-36,-30,-24,
-44,-25,-14,-35,-37,-15,26,-3,8,8,50,8,40,50,57,32,64,-93,-116,-136,-46,-11,
-14,-122,-65,-71,0,-171,-182,-173,-30,-163,-179,-321,-291,-290,-222,-263,-253,
-272,-266,-265,-279,-450,-463,-439,-435,-398,-415,-541,-517,-632,-434,-434,
-605,-581,-337]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7.
O-O Na6 8. d5 Nc5 9. Qc2 a5 10. Bg5 {Lures the pawn to h6 which might prevent
the black bishop from becoming active.} h6 11. Be3 b6 12. Nd2 {A solid
positional plan.} Bg4 13. f3 Bd7 14. b3 Nh5 15. Rfe1 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Yg7h6]} (
{If White continues with his standard queenside expansion:} 15. a3 {[%cal
Gb3b4] Then the second player can bring his pieces quickly into action with:}
Nf4 {[%csl Re2,Gf4]} 16. Rf2 h5 {[%cal Gg7h6,Gh5h4]} 17. Rb1 Bh6 {[%csl Re3]
[%cal Rf4h3]} 18. Nf1 a4 $1 19. bxa4 (19. b4 Nb3 {[%csl Gd4,Gf4][%cal Gb3d4]})
19... Nxa4 20. Nb5 f5 {[%csl Ra3,Rc4,Gf4,Gh6][%cal Gf5e4,Gh5h4] Levin,E (2505)
-Kryakvin,D (2554) Sochi 2016}) 15... Bf6 $3 $146 {[%csl Re3,Gf6,Gg5][%cal
Gf6g5] A star novelty. An idea by Smirin. It is pretty much the same as the
lines where Black is ready to part with a pawn in order to bring his bishop
into life on the long diagonal.} (15... Nf4 {was seen only prior to
Naumkin-Smirin.}) 16. g3 {Korobov did not dare to accept the sacrifice. With
the text move he prevents the knight jump on f4, but weakens his kingside in
the process.} ({The tactical justification of the line is:} 16. Bxh6 Bg5 $1 {
[%csl Gg5]} 17. Bxg5 {More or less forced.} ({Notice that the rook is immune:} 
17. Bxf8 $2 {As the superiority of the black pieces on the dark squares
becomes unbearable:} Be3+ 18. Kh1 (18. Kf1 Qh4 {[%cal Rh4f2]} 19. Nd1 Ng3+ 20.
hxg3 Qh1#) 18... Ng3+ $1 19. hxg3 Qxf8 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Rf8h6,Rh6h1,Re3g1]} 20.
Nf1 Qh6+ 21. Nh2 Kg7 $19 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Rh6h2,Ra8h8] With unstoppable mate.})
17... Qxg5 {For the pawn Black seized the dark squares and brought his pieces
closer to the enemy king by using the weakened points.} 18. Nf1 ({If:} 18. Bf1
Kg7 $5 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gf8h8,Gh5f4] /\ Rh8 and the h-file is another asset
for Black, a product of the pawn sacrifice.}) 18... f5 $44 {[%csl Rc4,Re2,Rf3,
Rg1][%cal Gf8f1,Gg5g1,Gh5f4,Re2c4,Re2f3] The strong Black pieces and
harmonious development compensate him with interest for the sacrificed pawn.}
19. exf5 ({If:} 19. Qc1 Nf4 20. g3 Nh3+ 21. Kg2 f4 {with an attack.}) 19...
gxf5 20. a3 {The natural desire to start play on his own on the queenside made
Naumkin's task even more difficult.} a4 $1 {A strong counter-blow.} (20... Nf4
21. g3) 21. b4 (21. bxa4 $5 {might have been White's last chance.}) 21... Nb3
$17 {[%csl Gb3,Rd4][%cal Gb3d4] The knight makes it do the d4 outpost and
Black's strategic advantage becomes frightening.} 22. Ra2 Rf7 23. g3 Kh8 $1 24.
Bd1 Rg8 25. Qb1 Qh4 $6 (25... Nd4 26. Rf2 (26. Qd3 f4 27. Ne4 Qg6 28. Rg2 fxg3
29. hxg3 Nf4 $1 $19) 26... Rh7 27. Bxa4 $2 Bxa4 28. Nxa4 Nxg3 $1 29. hxg3 (29.
Nxg3 f4) 29... Qh5 $19) 26. Bxb3 axb3 (26... Qd4+ 27. Kh1 (27. Re3 $2 axb3 28.
Qxb3 Nxg3 $1 (28... f4 29. Ne2) 29. hxg3 Rxg3+ 30. Nxg3 Qxe3+ 31. Kg2 Rg7 32.
Qb2 f4 33. Nce4 Bh3+ $1 34. Kxh3 Qxf3 $19) 27... Qxc3 $2 28. Re3 Qd4 29. Rd2
$18) 27. Rg2 $1 (27. Qxb3 $2 f4 28. Ne4 fxg3 29. hxg3 Nxg3 $19) 27... Qd4+ 28.
Re3 f4 29. Ne2 Qxc4 30. gxf4 (30. Qxb3 Qa6 31. gxf4 (31. Rc3 Bh3) 31... Rxg2+
32. Kxg2 exf4 {- 30.Qb3} 33. Re4 Nf6 $1 34. Qb2 Rg7+ $19) 30... Rxg2+ 31. Kxg2
exf4 $2 (31... Nxf4+ 32. Nxf4 Rxf4 33. Qxb3 Bh3+ $1) 32. Re4 (32. Qxb3 Rg7+ (
32... Qa6 {- 30.Qb3}) 33. Kh1 Qa6 34. Re4 Nf6) 32... Qxd5 $19 33. Kf2 Qg5 $6 (
33... c5 $1 34. Nc3 (34. Ke1 c4) 34... Qg5 35. Qxb3 Rg7 36. Ke1 Qh4+ $19) 34.
Ke1 Nf6 35. Qb2 $1 (35. Rxf4 Re7) 35... Kg8 36. Rxf4 Bb5 37. Nfg3 Bxe2 38. Nxe2
(38. Rf5 Qe3 39. Nxe2 Re7 $1 40. Rxf6 Qg1+ 41. Kd2 Rxe2+) 38... Re7 $1 39.
Qxb3+ Kg7 40. Rc4 $8 Qg1+ 41. Kd2 Qxh2 42. Qd3 c5 $1 43. Rc1 Kf7 44. bxc5 bxc5
45. a4 (45. Re1 d5 46. Kd1 Qf2 47. Rg1 Rxe2 48. Qg6+ Ke6) 45... Re5 $1 46. Qb5
Qf2 47. Rc3 d5 {[/\ c4] 0-1 (47) Naumkin,I (2500)-Smirin,I (2630) Ischia 1995
Informant 64 [Smirin,I]} (47... d5 48. Rxc5 Rxe2+ 49. Qxe2 Qxc5)) (16. a3 Bg5
17. Bf2 $2 Bxd2 18. Qxd2 Nxb3) 16... Bg5 {But now the bishop occupies the
diagonal for free.} 17. Bf2 Ng7 $1 {[%cal Gh6h5,Gh5h4] Another strong manoeuvre
which prepares the powerful h-pawn advance.} ({Weaker is the immediate:} 17...
f5 18. exf5 gxf5 19. f4 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Re2h5] As the knight on h5 is hanging.
}) 18. Rad1 ({After:} 18. h4 Be7 {[%csl Rg3,Rh4][%cal Gf7f5,Gf5f4] Black would
attack the weakened pawns with f7-f5-f4.}) 18... f5 {Here too Miroshnichenko
firmly seizes the initiative. White did not even have a chance to open a file
on the opposite wing yet and already has to start defending on the kingside.}
19. a3 f4 20. Kg2 h5 {[%csl Gf4,Rg2,Gh5][%cal Gh6h5,Gf5f4]} 21. Rh1 Qc8 22. b4
axb4 23. axb4 Bh3+ $17 {[%csl Rg2,Rh1] Disrupting the co-ordination of the
white pieces. Black's edge is indisputable.} 24. Kg1 {[%csl Rh1]} Nd7 25. Nb5
Ne8 26. Nb1 Ndf6 27. N1c3 Rf7 28. Qd3 Ng7 29. Bf1 Bxf1 30. Qxf1 Qd7 31. Qg2
Raf8 32. h3 fxg3 33. Bxg3 Nh7 34. Rd3 h4 35. Bf2 Nh5 36. Qg4 Qd8 37. Kf1 Nf4
38. Rd1 Be7 39. Ke1 Ng5 40. Bxh4 Nxf3+ $1 41. Qxf3 Ng2+ 42. Qxg2 Bxh4+ 43. Kd2
Rf2+ 44. Qxf2 Rxf2+ 45. Kd3 Qf8 46. c5 dxc5 47. bxc5 Qxc5 48. Rhf1 Rh2 49. Rf3
Bg5 50. Rg3 Qf2 51. Rdg1 Rxh3 0-1

﻿[Event "Candidates Tournament"]
