{[%evp 0,81,29,15,21,-20,43,43,48,48,48,18,18,3,27,22,66,69,55,56,45,67,86,0,
20,-6,-25,-10,-4,39,26,26,46,28,60,43,35,27,42,56,52,47,53,0,57,47,35,0,0,0,
106,88,82,76,65,53,124,43,76,91,155,65,65,72,86,61,63,71,58,58,56,64,45,42,92,
83,67,0,0,0,68,0,0,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O 6. Be3
e5 7. d5 c5 {A premature move.} ({Better was:} 7... c6 8. Qd2 cxd5 9. cxd5 Nbd7
10. Nge2 a6 {Here the sloppy maneuver:} 11. Nc1 $6 Nh5 12. Bd3 f5 13. N1e2 {
Allowed Kasparov a chance to execute the blockading idea with:} Ndf6 14. exf5
gxf5 15. Ng3 ({There is no sufficient counter-attack after:} 15. g4 fxg4 16.
fxg4 Nxg4) 15... e4 $1 {[%csl Ga1][%cal Gg7a1]} 16. Nxh5 Nxh5 17. fxe4 f4 $1 {
[%csl Ge5] Exactly the same way that Gligoric had executed it dozen of years
back. The control of the dark squares spelled trouble for White after:} 18. Bf2
Bg4 19. h3 Bd7 {[%csl Rg3]} 20. O-O-O Be5 $1 {[%csl Rd3,Ge5][%cal Re4e5]} 21.
Kb1 Qf6 {[%cal Gf6a1]} 22. Be2 Ng3 23. Bxg3 $6 fxg3 24. Bf3 Rac8 $17 {[%csl
Rb1][%cal Rh8a1,Rc8c3,Gb7b5,Gb5b4] Gheorgiu-Kasparov, Saloniki ol. 1988.}) 8.
Bd3 ({Nowadays it is known that White needs to prevent the knight maneuver
with:} 8. g4 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Rg4h5,Rf6h5]} Ne8 9. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} f5 10.
gxf5 gxf5 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Rd3,Rf5] Thanks to the firm control
over the e4 square White is clearly better.}) 8... Nh5 $1 {The most aggressive
set-up.} 9. Nge2 f5 10. exf5 gxf5 11. Qc2 ({White can also develop the queen
with:} 11. Qd2 {The Black may proceed with normal development:} Nd7 ({Or
prepare a warm welcome for the white king on the queenside with:} 11... a6 $5 {
[%cal Gb7b5]} 12. a4 ({Since:} 12. O-O-O b5 $1 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Ra8a2] does
not seem particularly appealing for the first player.}) ({Whereas:} 12. Ng3 Qe8
$1 13. Nxh5 Qxh5 14. O-O-O {Can be still met with the blockading idea:} (14.
O-O {is safer} Nd7 15. f4 Rb8 16. a4) 14... e4 $1 {[%csl Re4]} 15. fxe4 f4 $1 {
[%csl Rd2,Rd3,Re3]} 16. Bf2 Nd7 17. g3 f3 18. g4 Qe8 19. g5 Ne5 $44 {[%csl Yd3,
Re5][%cal Gg7e5,Ge8e5] With huge compensation for a pawn.}) 12... Nd7 13. Bg5
Qe8 14. O-O Ndf6 15. Bc2 Bd7 $132 {Black is fine in the arising position.}) 12.
Bg5 Qe8 {The queen supports the e5-e4 advance, for example:} 13. Nb5 $140 e4 $1
14. fxe4 Ne5 {[%csl Ge5]} 15. O-O ({But not:} 15. Nc7 Qg6 16. Nxa8 fxe4 17. Bc2
Nxc4 18. Qc1 Bg4 {[%csl Gc4,Re1,Gg4,Gg6,Gg7,Gh5] where despite the rook
deficit Black is crushing his opponent.}) 15... Nxd3 {After:} 16. Qxd3 fxe4 17.
Qe3 Qg6 18. Rxf8+ Bxf8 19. Rf1 Bd7 $11 {Black does not experience any problems.
}) 11... e4 $1 {[%cal Rh8a1] The star idea of the game and a pawn sacrifice
that neatly summarizes the KID. In the battle for the centre, Black often
blocks his own bishop with the e7-e5 advance. This move is needed to gain
space in the centre but unfortunately locks the KID pride and honour.  This
fact alone does not mean that the second player will abandon his attempts to
bring the bishop into life. As you will notice Black has more than one way of
bringing this problematic piece into the action. The central pawn sacrifice
remains however the most beautiful and powerful one. Let's not forget another
important detail in the ensuing battle. White also had to limit one of his pieces
while fighting for the centre- his light-squared bishop. The move in the game
aims for the liberation of the black bishop and additionally fights against the
white problematic bishop, further limiting it with its own pawns.} 12. fxe4 f4
$1 {[%csl Rd3,Ge5]} 13. Bf2 ({Kotov probably should have given back the pawn
at once, and even sacrificed a piece with:} 13. e5 fxe3 14. Bxh7+ Kh8 15. e6 {
When Black has a bunch of interesting options:} Nf4 $5 (15... Rf2 $5) (15...
Nc6 $5 16. dxc6 bxc6 $132 {[%csl Re6][%cal Rc8e6]}) (15... Qh4+ $5 16. g3 Nxg3
17. Nxg3 Qxh7 $13)) 13... Nd7 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7e5] The e5 square is a
nice stepping stone for almost all black pieces.} 14. Ng1 {[%csl Rd7,Rg1][%cal
Gg1f3] In return Kotov is looking for a way to lift the blockade.} ({It is
late for liberation:} 14. e5 $6 Nxe5 15. Bxh7+ Kh8 $36 16. O-O-O Qg5 17. Kb1
Qxg2 18. Ne4 Nf6 19. Rhg1 Qf3 20. Nxf6 Rxf6 21. Nc3 Qh5 22. Be4 Bg4 $15 {
[%csl Ge5,Gg4] and Black is clearly better thanks to his active pieces.}) 14...
Qg5 15. Bf1 Ne5 $44 {[%csl Ge5,Yf1,Yg1,Gg5,Yh1,Gh5] For the pawn Black managed
to free all his pieces and they are now occupying dominant central squares.}
16. Nf3 Qe7 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. O-O-O Nf6 19. h3 Bd7 ({An even better plan was
the immediate queenside attack with:} 19... a6 $5 20. Bd3 ({Or:} 20. a4 $5 Bd7
21. Re1 Nh5 $36 {[%cal Gh5g3,Gb7b5,Rh8a1]}) 20... b5 21. cxb5 axb5 22. Bxb5 Ba6
$40 {[%cal Gf8b8,Gb8b2,Ga8a2,Rg7a1]}) ({Or even the second pawn sacrifice with:
} 19... b5 $5 20. cxb5 a6 21. a4 axb5 22. Bxb5 Bd7 23. Rhe1 Bxb5 24. Nxb5 Nh5
$36) 20. Bd3 a6 21. Nb1 $1 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f3,Rf3e5] Another excellent
maneuver by the Russian player. The second knight is heading to the
anti-blocking square.} {However:} f3 $3 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Rg2f3,Rb1d2,Rd2f3]
Ruins the plan and opens another square for the black pieces.} ({There was no
time for:} 21... b5 $140 $6 22. Nd2 {[%csl Re5,Rf3][%cal Rd2f3,Rf3e5]}) ({
Although both:} 21... Rae8 $5 22. Rde1 (22. Nd2 Ba4 $1 23. b3 (23. Qxa4 Nxe4 $1
{[%csl Rb2,Rf2][%cal Ge4f2,Re5b2]}) 23... Qa1+ 24. Nb1 Bd7 25. Rde1 b5 $11)
22... Nh5 23. Nd2 Ng3 24. Nf3 Qh5 25. Rhg1 b5 $132 {with counterplay.}) ({
Or the bishop improvement with:} 21... Be8 $5 {[%csl Rd1,Re4][%cal Ge8g6,Gg6e4,
Gg6h5,Rh5d1]} 22. Nd2 Ba4 $1 {Would have promised Black enough play too:} 23.
b3 (23. Qxa4 Nxe4) 23... Qa1+ 24. Nb1 Be8 $1 25. Be1 Nd7 26. e5 $5 Bxe5 27.
Bxh7+ Kh8 28. Bd3 Rg8 $13) 22. gxf3 Nh5 23. Nd2 Nf4 {[%csl Rc1,Rd2,Rd3,Ge5,Gf4,
Gg7][%cal Gg7a1,Gf4d3,Gf4e2,Gf4g2,Rd2f3,Rd2e4,Rd3e4] The triumph of Black
strategy! White's extra pawns only limit his pieces and do not cover the
excellent outposts close to his position. Gligoric's pieces posses enormous
energy which compensates the material with interest.} 24. Bf1 b5 $1 {[%cal
Gb8b2]} 25. h4 Kh8 26. Rg1 Bf6 27. Nb3 Rab8 ({The logical continuation:} 27...
b4 $1 {Would have forced White to fight for his life with:} 28. Be3 $1 ({After:
} 28. Na5 Ba4 29. b3 {Black can force a draw with:} Qa1+ ({Or play for more
with:} 29... Bd7 $5 {[%csl Ya5][%cal Gf6d8,Ra6a5,Ra5a4,Ra4b3,Ra8a1]}) 30. Kd2
Bc3+ 31. Ke3 Bd4+ $11) 28... a5 29. Qd2 Bxh4 30. Nd4 $1 {It is this resource
that saves White. Otherwise the a-pawn advance would have decisively weakened
the white king.} Ng6 31. Be2 (31. f4 $143 Nxf4 32. Nf3 Nd3+ 33. Bxd3 Rxf3 $17)
31... Bf6 ({Or:} 31... Nf4 32. Nc6 Qf6 33. Bf1 Ng6 34. f4 $1 Nxf4 35. e5 $1
dxe5 36. Bxc5 Rfe8 $13 {In all these lines Black's play seems easier.}) 32. f4
Qxe4 33. Bd3 Qxe3 34. Qxe3 Bxd4 35. Qd2 Nxf4 36. Rh1 Nxd3+ 37. Qxd3 Bf5 38. Qg3
Be5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5][%cal Gf5b1,Ge5a1,Ge5g7,Gf5h7,Ya5a4,Ya4a3,Ya8e8,Ya8b8]} 39.
Qe3 a4 40. Rdf1 a3 41. b3 Rae8 $44 {Black does not risk to lose.}) 28. Be1 (28.
Bg3 bxc4 $1 29. Bxc4 a5 $1 30. Qh2 Bg7 31. Bxf4 Rxf4 32. Rg5 Qf6 $44) 28... b4
29. Kb1 Ra8 30. Bg3 Rg8 31. Qh2 $2 (31. Qd2 $1 Rxg3 32. Rxg3 Ne2 33. Bxe2 Qxg3
34. f4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4][%cal Ge4e5]}) 31... Rxg3 32. Rxg3 Ne2 33. Qxe2
Qxg3 34. Nc1 a5 35. Nd3 Bd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4]} 36. h5 Qh4 37. Bg2 Rg8 38. Rh1 Qg3
39. Bf1 a4 40. Kc2 $2 a3 (40... b3+ $1 41. axb3 axb3+ 42. Kxb3 Qg7 $1 43. h6 (
43. Kc2 Rb8 (43... Ba4+ $5) 44. Kb1 Ba4 45. Rh2 Qa7 $1 $17 {[%csl Yb1]}) 43...
Ba4+ 44. Ka2 (44. Kxa4 Qb7 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Rg8a8,Ra8a4]}) 44... Qa7 45. Kb1
Bb3 46. Nc1 Ra8 47. Nxb3 Qa2+ 48. Kc1 Qxb3 $17) 41. b3 1/2-1/2

