{[%evp 0,83,28,27,27,3,48,7,7,7,9,20,26,-14,-11,-11,37,10,27,27,52,52,58,49,66,
29,22,24,23,13,23,28,45,56,34,48,69,75,58,58,55,58,36,20,18,19,40,36,100,107,
107,106,132,136,161,144,144,150,204,212,217,257,251,251,251,249,266,263,332,
341,475,403,484,507,511,332,464,517,516,442,442,442,445,444,436,445]} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 g6 3. f3 {A very popular Anti-Gruenfeld line.} c5 4. d5 d6 {A recent top
GM game took a highly exciting course:} (4... b5 5. e4 Bg7 6. e5 Ng8 7. f4 d6
8. Nf3 {Aronian,L (2797)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2758) Beijing 2014}) 5. e4 Bg7 6.
Ne2 O-O 7. Nec3 {Some years back the many time Bulgarian champion GM E.
Ermenkov was trying to convince me that this is the best set-up against the
KID. He even came to the conclusion that the whole defence is dead on the
account of this tricky development. The idea is to once and for all solve the
problem of this knight (which often finds itself on squares like h1 on its way
to the centre), then finish the development with Bc1-e3 and Nb1-d2 when all
the white pieces will be well placed and finally smash Black on either side of
the board. However, there is an obvious drawback of this whole system-White
lags in development. Even though the position is closed, Li founds a way to
exploit this.} e5 8. g4 (8. Be3 {was not tested yet.}) (8. Bg5 $5) 8... h5 $146
{[%csl Gh5][%cal Gh7h5] "A strong idea." (Harikrishna) In a previous game
Black found himself suffering after:} (8... Ne8 9. h4 f5 10. Be3 (10. h5 $5 {
[%csl Rg8][%cal Rh5g6]}) 10... Nd7 11. Nd2 Bf6 12. g5 $1 {[%csl Rg5]} Be7 13.
exf5 gxf5 14. Qc2 {[%csl Rf5,Rg8] Arencibia Rodriguez,W (2335)-Boudy Bueno,J 
(2390) Havana 1986}) 9. h3 Nh7 $1 {[%cal Gg7f6,Gf6g5] The point behind Li
Chao's play. He wants to trade the dark-squared bishops.} 10. Be3 ({Both
players came to the conclusion that Black is doing good after} 10. h4 Bf6 11.
gxh5 (11. g5 Bg7 {[%cal Gf7f6]}) 11... Bxh4+ 12. Kd2 g5 13. Kc2) (10. gxh5 {
is not good on the account of} Qh4+ {[%csl Re1,Rh5][%cal Rh4h5,Rh4e1]} 11. Kd2
Qxh5 $15) 10... h4 {Sticking to his original idea.} ({Li also considered} 10...
f5 11. gxf5 gxf5 12. Qe2 f4 13. Bf2 Bf6 14. h4 Kh8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f8,Gf8g6]
followed by the knight transfer from b8 to g6.}) 11. Qd2 Bf6 12. Rg1 Bg5 13.
Bxg5 Qxg5 {[%csl Gf4,Gg5] Black can be happy with the opening outcome. In fact,
he thought he is already better. Li managed to trade his "bad" bishop and if
he can keep the white one blocked he can be quite optimistic about the future.}
(13... Nxg5 {was another idea with equality after} 14. Qf2 Kg7 15. Nd2 Rh8 16.
f4 exf4 17. Qxf4 f6 {[%csl Ge5,Gf6,Gg5,Gh4] (Harikrishna)} ({But not the hasty
} 17... Qf6 $2 18. Qxf6+ Kxf6 19. Nb5 {[%csl Rc7,Rd6][%cal Rb5c7,Rb5d6]}) ({Or
} 17... a6 {[%cal Gd8f6] which prepares Qd8-f6 (Li)})) 14. Nb5 {White wants to
make sure he can do something on the kingside.} (14. Qxg5 Nxg5 {[%csl Gc8,Gd4,
Ge3,Rf1,Gf4,Gg3,Gg5] is indeed pleasant advantage for Black.}) 14... Qe7 15. g5
a6 (15... Nd7 $5 {at once makes sense too.}) 16. N5c3 Nd7 17. Qg2 {Both
players are getting ready for the opening of the kingside.} Kg7 (17... f6 18.
gxf6 Rxf6 19. Qg4 g5 20. Qxh4 Rxf3 $11) 18. Nd2 f6 19. gxf6+ Qxf6 {[%csl Rf4]
[%cal Gf8f7,Gg6g5,Rd7f8,Rf8g6,Rg6f4] Black's plan is Rf8-f7,g6-g5 followed by
Nd7-f8-g6 after which he will be in full command on the kingside. However,
Harikrishna found a strong antidot.} ({After} 19... Rxf6 20. Qg4 {[%csl Rg6,
Rh4][%cal Rg4h4,Rg4g6] one of the black kingside pawns will drop.}) 20. Nd1 $1
{[%csl Gf5,Gg4][%cal Gd1e3,Ge3f5,Ge3g4] Li Chao missed this idea. Now the
knight comes to an excellent position from where it supports the demolition of
the blockade.} Rf7 21. Nf2 Ndf8 ({In case of} 21... g5 22. Nd3 Kh6 {Black did
not like} 23. Be2 {with the idea} Ndf8 ({Or} 23... Qg6 24. f4 $1 {[%csl Rf4]
[%cal Re2h5]} exf4 25. Nf3 {and if} Qxe4 $2 26. Nxg5 Qxg2 27. Nxf7+ $18) 24. f4
$3 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Re2h5]} gxf4 (24... exf4 25. e5 dxe5 {[%csl Ge4,Re5,Gf3,
Rf4,Gf5,Gg4,Rg5,Rh4,Gh5]} 26. Ne4 f3 27. Qf2 $1 {with advantage. Rather than} (
27. Nxf6 $2 fxg2 28. Nxh7 Nxh7 {which is actually good for Black.})) 25. Qf3
Ng6 26. Qh5+ Kg7 27. Nf3 $18 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Rf3h4,Rg1g7] and there is no
defense (Li Chao).}) 22. Nd3 b5 {White will break the blockade in case of:} (
22... g5 23. f4 $1 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf3f4]} exf4 24. e5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Re5,Gf3]
[%cal Ge4e5,Gd2e4,Gd2f3]} (24. Nf3 Kh6 25. Be2 Ng6) 24... dxe5 25. Ne4 {
[%csl Ge4,Rf6,Rg5][%cal Re4f6,Ge4g5] and establish an attacking blockade
himself.Indeed this seems unpleasant for the second player, but is everything
that bad? After} Qh6 {Black has many pieces ready to challenge the blockade in
their turn and this should be good enough to keep the game unclear. For
example:} 26. O-O-O (26. Ndxc5 g4 $1 27. hxg4 b6 28. Nd3 Ng5) (26. Nexc5 Bf5 $1
) 26... f3 (26... Bf5 $5) 27. Qh2 g4+ 28. Rd2 g3 29. Nxg3 hxg3 30. Rxg3+ Kh8
31. Nxe5 {and it's anyone's game.}) 23. O-O-O g5 $2 {Only this move can be
named a mistake.} ({Instead Harikrishna's recommendation} 23... bxc4 24. Nxc4
Bd7 25. Ne3 (25. f4 exf4 26. e5 dxe5 27. Ncxe5 $6 (27. Ndxe5 f3) 27... c4 $1)
25... g5 {keeps the game approximately even.} ({Or even} 25... Qxf3)) (23...
Bd7 {is another option} 24. f4 exf4 25. e5 dxe5 26. Ne4 f3 27. Qh2 (27. Qf2 $5)
27... Qe7 (27... Qf5 $2 28. Nd6) 28. d6 {when anything can happen.}) 24. f4 $1
{[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf3f4] This is very strong now. The white pieces get an
access to the enemy king.} exf4 25. e5 $1 Qf5 {Sadly, the pawn should be
allowed to go to e6 as otherwise, Black's position will quickly deteriorate after}
(25... dxe5 26. Ne4 Qh6 (26... Qe7 27. d6) 27. Nxe5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5,Rg7][%cal
Rd5d6,Rd6d7]}) 26. e6 {[%csl Ra8,Rc8] The pawn separates the flanks and this
is the reason why Li Chao cannot hold on the kingside.} f3 (26... Re7 27. Qe4 {
(Harikrishna)} (27. Ne4) 27... Kf6 28. Nf2 $1 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gf2g4] would
win for White.}) (26... bxc4 27. Nxc4 f3 28. Qd2 (28. Qh2) 28... Qxd5 29. Qc3+
Rf6 30. Nf4 {[%cal Rc3g7,Rg1g7] (Svidler)} ({Or the simple} 30. e7 {are two
other winning lines.})) ({PerhapsBlack's last chance was to sacrifice the
piece at once with} 26... Nxe6 27. dxe6 Bb7 28. Qf2 Qxe6 {although this should
also be won for the Indian GM.}) 27. Qh2 {Better than} (27. Nxf3 Qxf3 28. exf7
Qe3+ 29. Kb1 bxc4 {followed by c4-c3 (Harikrishna)} (29... Bxh3)) 27... Bxe6 (
27... Re7 28. Qxd6 $18) 28. dxe6 Qxe6 29. Nf2 Qe3 ({Maybe} 29... Rd8 30. Bd3 {
was a try for Black.}) 30. Ng4 Qf4 31. Qxf4 Rxf4 32. Nxf3 $1 {A small tactic
to get rid of Black's most dangerous pawn. The game is essentially over.} bxc4
(32... Rxf3 33. Bg2 $18) 33. Ngh2 Ne6 34. Rxd6 Nd4 (34... Re8 35. Rxa6) 35.
Rd7+ Kh8 36. Ne5 Nf8 37. Rf7 Re4 38. Rxg5 Rd8 39. Rxf8+ Rxf8 40. Ng6+ Kg7 41.
Nxf8+ Kxf8 42. Rxc5 1-0

