{[%evp 0,71,25,17,27,-4,22,22,23,32,37,18,24,9,56,54,41,34,20,-2,34,7,35,7,46,
18,55,41,41,41,42,36,44,43,41,41,36,74,62,55,75,138,155,152,153,143,172,180,
204,201,204,202,194,201,186,222,236,193,193,193,206,235,247,243,251,226,299,
306,320,261,335,326,335,328]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g3 c6
6. e4 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. h3 Re8 10. Be3 a5 11. Qc2 a4 12. Rfd1 Qa5 13.
Rab1 exd4 14. Nxd4 Nc5 {[%csl Rc4,Gc5,Gf6][%cal Ga5b4,Ga4a3,Gc5e4,Gf6e4,Rb4c4]}
15. b4 axb3 16. axb3 Qb4 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5] In the Fianchettoed system Black is
often heading for an aggressive blockade as in the game. The queen on b4
together with the knight on c5 and eventually rook on a8 exert strong pressure
against the white queenside. One thing that Black enjoys in this line is the
fact that his queenside pieces may enter the game without even making a single
move, just like the white queenside bishop and rook in the Ruy Lopez.} 17. Bf4
$1 {[%csl Rd6] On the other hand Black should not forget that if the blockade
is lifted the organic weaknesses in his position (less space, weakness on d6)
might be exposed. With the neat manoeuvre in the game Kortschnoi skillfully
spoils the opponent's co-ordination.} ({It is interesting that even many years
after the model game by the legendary Viktor Lvovich people still do not know
his blockade-lifting method.} 17. Qd2 {Worked well in the following game:} Nfd7
18. Bf4 Ne6 19. Nxe6 Bxc3 20. Nc7 Bxd2 21. Bxd2 Qb6 22. Nxe8 Ra3 ({However
Black could have defended much better with:} 22... Ne5 $13) 23. Be3 Qd8 24.
Nxd6 $16 Qf8 25. Rd2 Ra8 26. Rbd1 h5 27. Nxc8 Rxc8 28. Rxd7 Qb4 29. Rd8+ Rxd8
30. Rxd8+ Kh7 31. h4 c5 32. Bf1 b6 33. Bg5 Qxb3 34. Bf6 g5 35. hxg5 Qb1 36.
Rh8+ {1-0 (40) Kveinys,A (2555)-Okuniewski,B (2265) Krynica 1997}) ({Ideas
like:} 17. Na2 Qa5 18. Ra1 Ncxe4 {are too far from the truth.}) 17... Bf8 {
The bishop is forced away from the active diagonal.} 18. Bd2 {[%cal Rc3d5] It
is the queen's term.} Qb6 19. Be3 {[%cal Re3b6,Rb3b4]} Qb4 {[%csl Ge3]} 20. Qd2
$1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gd4c2,Rc2b4]} Qb6 ({Obviously:} 20... Nfxe4 {loses to:} 21.
Nxe4 {[%cal Rd2b4,Re4d2]}) ({Whereas:} 20... Na6 {is bad due to:} 21. Nc2 Qa5
22. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Rf6][%cal Rd2a5,Rd5f6] when Black cannot defend
everything at the same time:} Qd8 23. Bb6) ({Finally, the return to the long
diagonal:} 20... Bg7 {Is strongly met by:} 21. e5 $1 ({The text move is even
better than:} 21. Nc2 Nfxe4 22. Nxe4 Qxd2 23. Nxd2 Bf5 $1 24. Rbc1 Nd3 25. g4
Nxc1 26. Rxc1 Bxc2 27. Rxc2 $16 {which also promises advantage to White.})
21... dxe5 22. Nc2 Nxb3 23. Nxb4 Nxd2 24. Rxd2 $16 {(All lines by Sakaev and
Landa.)}) 21. b4 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Re3b6] Once that the queen was forced away
from its idea position Kortschoi launches decisive counter-attack. Notice that
the hero queen is quickly turned into a sinner.} Ncxe4 22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23. Qd3 {
[%cal Rd3e4,Gd4e6,Gd4c6,Gd4f5,Gd4b5]} Nxf2 ({Or:} 23... f5 24. Ne6 {[%csl Rc7]
[%cal Re6c7]}) ({If:} 23... d5 24. Ne6 c5 25. Nxf8 Rxf8 26. cxd5 {[%csl Rc5]
[%cal Gb4c5] and Black's position collapses.}) ({Finally:} 23... Nf6 24. Ne6
Qxe3 25. Qxe3 Bxe6 26. Qb6 $1 $16 {does not yield Black enough for the queen. 
(Landa, Sakaev)}) 24. Bxf2 Qc7 25. Re1 Rxe1+ 26. Rxe1 Bd7 27. b5 $1 h5 28. bxc6
bxc6 29. Nb5 Qb8 ({Against:} 29... Qd8 {Best is:} 30. Nc3 $1 $16 ({Although:} 
30. Na7 Qc7 31. Ra1 $16 {might be good enough too.}) ({But not:} 30. Nxd6 $2
Bf5 $2)) 30. Nxd6 $1 {A small combination that finishes the game.} Qxd6 31.
Qxd6 Bxd6 32. Rd1 Be6 33. Rxd6 Bxc4 34. Bd4 Be6 35. Bxc6 Rc8 36. h4 1-0

