1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 (3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 Bf5
8. d5 Na5 9. Nd4 Bd7 10. Qd3 Ng4 11. f4 $5 $146 c5 (11... c6 {/\ Qb6}) 12. Nc2
{[#]This position is similar to the one which arises in the Yugoslav Variation.
Mikhail Tal wrote about the a5-knight once, that its position can be either
active or bad. This usually depends on the success of Black's actions against
the c4-pawn. White's plan is to keep this pawn and prepare play on the
kingside and in the centre, where the a5-knight might be missed.} a6 13. b3 b5
{[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb5c4,Ga5c4]} 14. Rb1 Rb8 15. Bd2 Qc7 16. h3 bxc4 17. bxc4 Nf6
{[%csl Ra5] 17...Nh6 18 e4 f5 would have been worse for Black, as that would
start some action in the centre, where White is stronger.} 18. e4 Rxb1 19. Rxb1
Rb8 20. Ne3 Rxb1+ 21. Qxb1 Be8 22. Bf1 $1 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gf1d3] The
light-squared bishop will be better off on d3, where it will protect the
c4-pawn, giving freedom to the e3-knight.} Nh5 23. Kh2 Qb7 24. Qc2 Qc7 25. Bd3
Nb7 26. Ne2 Nf6 27. Ng1 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Gf3][%cal Gg1f3,Ge4e5]} Nd7 28. Nf3 Qb6
29. Nd1 Qc7 30. Kg2 Nb6 31. Ne3 Na4 32. Ng4 Qb6 33. e5 Qb2 34. Qxb2 Nxb2 35.
Be2 Na4 36. Nf2 {[#]White holds a positional edge, due to his space advantage.}
f6 {This desperate try is very risky - it allows White to seize even more
space.} (36... Bd7 37. g4 $1 e6 38. Ne4 {[%csl Rb7,Ge4]}) 37. e6 f5 $8 38. Nd1
Nb6 39. g4 Ba4 40. Ne3 Bd4 41. gxf5 Bxe3 42. Bxe3 gxf5 43. Bd3 Na5 44. Nd2 Be8
45. Bf2 Bg6 46. Be1 Kf8 47. Kf3 h6 48. Ke3 Ke8 49. Be2 Kf8 50. Kd3 {[%csl Ge1,
Ge2,Rf5][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3f5]} Be8 {[#]Here White's task is to manage to
move the knight on e3, after which the position will be winning for him, as
the dark-squared bishop will be able to hit the a5-knight, releasing pressure
from the c4-pawn, and then the weakness on f5 will fall. In the game, White
managed to complete this plan, although it's possible that Black could have
put up more resistance.} 51. Kc3 Na4+ 52. Kc2 Nb6 53. Bh4 Bg6 54. Kc3 Na4+ 55.
Kd3 Nb6 56. Bd1 Be8 57. Bc2 Bh5 58. Bf2 Be8 59. Be1 Kg7 60. Bb3 Bh5 61. Nf1 Nb7
(61... Nbxc4 $2 62. Bxc4 Nxc4 63. Ng3 $18) (61... Nxb3 $142) 62. Ne3 $18 Bg6
63. Bc2 Kf8 64. Kc3 Na5 65. Bd3 Be8 66. Nxf5 Bg6 67. Ne3 Be8 68. f5 Bh5 69. Bh4
Na4+ 70. Kc2 Nb6 71. f6 exf6 72. Bxf6 Nc8 73. Kc3 Nb7 74. Nf5 Bg6 75. Nxh6 Bxd3
76. Kxd3 Ne7 77. Bxe7+ Kxe7 78. Ng4 {1-0 (78) Baburin,A (2545)-Hakki,I (2380)
Yerevan 1996 CBM 055 [Baburin,A]}) 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7.
d5 Na5 8. Nd2 c5 {[%csl Ya5][%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Ya5c4,Yb5c4]} 9. Qc2 a6 10. O-O
Bf5 $146 ({White's strategy prevailed in another world champion's game:} 10...
Rb8 11. a3 Qc7 12. Rb1 Bd7 13. Nce4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Rbc8 15. b3 b5 16. h4 Bf5 17.
h5 e6 18. h6 Bh8 19. Rd1 e5 20. f3 Nb7 21. g4 {Smyslov, V-Liublinsky, V Moscow
1950}) 11. e4 Bd7 12. b3 b5 {Geller is consistently trying to generate play on
the queenside while the opponent tries to catch up with his development.} 13.
Bb2 bxc4 14. bxc4 Rb8 15. Rab1 Rb4 16. a3 {The critical moment of the game.
Geller failed to appreciate it and timidly retreated.} Rb8 ({Nowadays people
recognize the long-term danger of the excluded knight and try to bring it into
life as quick as possible, even at the expense of an exchange with:} 16... Rxc4
17. Nxc4 Nxc4 18. Bc1 Qa5) 17. Nd1 $1 {[%cal Gd1e3,Ra1h8,Gf2f4,Ge4e5] A
trademark regroupment. The pawn structure favours White in his play for the
centre and on the kingside and Botvinnik brings his knight into the optimal
square. In the process, he secures the c4 pawn, opens the diagonal for his
bishop and prepares the attack against the a5 knight via the c3 square.} Qc7
18. Ne3 Rb7 19. Bc3 Rfb8 20. h3 {Last preparation before the final advance in
the centre. Notice that White does not mind trading the rooks. One of the
standard plans when playing against an excluded piece is to swap off the
superfluous pieces. Then the difference between the remaining pieces becomes
more obvious.  Without the rooks on the board, there will be no more
counterplay on the b-file for Black, and the knight on a5 will be completely
out of the picture. Whereas the remaining queens will still promise White
enough attacking chances on the kingside.} Rxb1 21. Rxb1 Rxb1+ 22. Nxb1 Qb6 23.
Nd2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5]} Ne8 ({Instead:} 23... e5 $5 {to slow down White was
Botvinnik's suggestion. But there too White is significantly better after:}
24. dxe6 Bxe6 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ga5c6,Gc6d4]} 25. Nd5 Nxd5 26. cxd5 Bd7 27. Bxg7
Kxg7 28. Qc3+ f6 29. f4 $16) 24. Bxg7 Nxg7 25. Kh2 Ne8 26. f4 Nf6 ({Perhaps
Geller should have tried:} 26... f6 27. Qc3 Nb7 {With the idea to meet:} 28. e5
({But White can attack instead with:} 28. h4 $5 $16) 28... fxe5 29. fxe5 {With:
} dxe5 $5 30. Qxe5 {When:} Qf6 {generates counter-play for Black after:} (30...
Qd6 31. Qb2 Qc7 32. d6 $5 Nbxd6 33. Qe5 {[%csl Re7,Yg8][%cal Ge3d5]}) 31. Qb8
Nbd6 32. Qa7 Qf2 33. Ndf1 (33. Nef1 Nf6 34. Qxa6 Bf5) 33... Bf5 $132 {As:} 34.
Qxe7 $2 {loses to:} Be4) 27. e5 {The start of the decisive attack.} Ne8 28. Qc3
f6 $2 ({Black is losing in all the lines:} 28... Ba4 29. Ng4 h5 30. Nh6+ Kg7
31. e6+ $1 f6 (31... Kxh6 32. Qh8#) 32. Nf7 Nb3 33. f5 Qa5 (33... Nxd2 34. Qxd2
g5 35. Qe2 {and mates.}) 34. Ne4 gxf5 (34... Qxc3 35. Nxc3 {[%csl Ra4]}) 35.
Qe3 $1 {mate in four.}) (28... Nb7 29. e6 (29. h4 $5) (29. g4 $5) 29... fxe6 (
29... Ba4 30. exf7+ Kxf7 31. Qh8 Nf6 32. Ng4 $18 (32. Ne4 $18)) 30. dxe6 Bxe6
31. f5 (31. Nd5 Qd8 $11) 31... gxf5 (31... Bxf5 32. Nxf5 gxf5 33. Bd5+ e6 34.
Bxe6+ Kf8 35. Qh8+ Ke7 36. Bxf5 $18) 32. Nd5 Qd8 (32... Qa5 $1 33. Qe3 (33.
Nxe7+ $6 Kf7) 33... Ng7 34. Nxe7+ Kf8 35. Nxf5 Bxf5 36. Bxb7 $16) 33. Nf4 Bc8
34. Bd5+ e6 35. Nxe6 Bxe6 36. Bxe6+ Kf8 37. Qh8+ Ke7 38. Bd5 $18) 29. e6 {
[%csl Ya5,Yb6,Gc4,Gd5,Yd7,Ge6,Re7,Rg8] Separates the black king from the
remaining pieces. The end is near.} Ba4 30. Be4 Ng7 ({Since:} 30... Nb3 {
loses the knight on the pin:} 31. Qb2 Qa5 (31... Nc7 32. Bc2) 32. Nxb3 Qe1 33.
Qd2 $18) 31. Bd3 Nh5 32. Be2 Ng7 33. h4 Ne8 34. Bd3 Ng7 35. f5 $1 {The same
merciless strategy.} Nb3 36. Qb2 Qa5 37. Nxb3 Qe1 38. Ng2 Qd1 39. Nc1 gxf5 40.
Be2 Qd4 41. Qxd4 1-0

