{[%evp 0,85,23,27,30,-14,52,57,41,35,45,37,34,8,12,9,9,16,42,23,20,15,26,47,15,
25,35,19,23,-2,7,22,64,69,78,87,87,60,117,100,118,102,110,103,120,103,99,99,
110,110,143,148,149,145,154,141,153,150,236,224,224,224,227,227,226,203,198,
200,237,259,261,257,257,265,259,257,301,261,308,286,298,289,361,372,597,614,
614,621]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 (5. h3 O-O 6. Bg5 Na6
7. Nf3 e5 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Nd5 Rd6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. b4 {In
general, the pawn structure after the trade of the d-pawns in the centre
favours Black. The reason is that the more modest development of the c6 pawn
secures better control of the central outposts by the black pieces. Black has
two wonderful squares for his knights on f4 and especially on d4. At the same
time White struggles to find a good outpost for his knights.} c6 {[%csl Gc6,
Rd4,Ge5,Gf4][%cal Ge5d4,Ge5f4,Gc6d5,Rc4d5,Re4d5]} 13. Nxf6+ {White probably
wants to make a draw and rest a bit, but this is not the right approach. Any
KID player will assure you that the resulting endgame might bring trouble only
for White.} (13. c5 $2 Rxd5 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Rf3][%cal Rf6a1,Re5e4] 0-1 Ristic,N 
(2405)-Pikula,D (2330)/Cetinje 1993/EXT 2002 (35)}) 13... Rxf6 {Diagram [#]
White has indeed more space, but his position is strategically lost. The gain
of space discovered some weaknesses in his camp, namely the d4- square. At the
same time the analogical square on d5 is well covered by the black pieces and
is unreachable for the white knight.} 14. a3 c5 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Rf1] This fixes
the white pawns on the colour of his own bishop and prepares a standard
knight manoeuvre.} 15. b5 Nc7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc7e6,Ge6d4]} 16. Be2 (16. Nxe5
{does not bring relief due to-} Re6 17. Ng4 f5 18. Ne3 f4 19. Nd5 Nxd5 20. cxd5
Rxe4+ $15) ({while} 16. Rd1 Re6 17. Rd8+ {only helps Black to proceed with his
idea-} Kg7 18. Be2 Re7 $15 {[%cal Gc7e6]}) 16... Re6 17. O-O-O Re8 $15 {
Diagram [#] White can do nothing to face the establishment of the black knight
on d4. After this Black can either prepare the f5 breakthrough, or he can even
open the position on the queen's flank at the proper moment.} (17... Kg7 18. a4
a6 {Probably not familiar with the previous game Polgar rushes up and throws
away the edge. Now White uses the open a-file to release the pressure.} 19. Kb2
Re7 20. Rd6 Ne8 21. Rd5 axb5 22. axb5 b6 23. Ra1 Rxa1 24. Kxa1 f6 25. Rd8 Bb7
26. Nd2 f5 27. exf5 gxf5 {[%emt 0:00:37] 1/2-1/2 Huebner,R (2605)-Polgar,J 
(2630)/Biel 1993/CBM}) 18. Rhe1 f6 19. Rd6 Kf7 20. Nd2 Ke7 21. Rd3 Ne6 {
[%csl Gd4,Re2,Ge6][%cal Ge6d4]} 22. g3 h5 23. h4 Nd4 24. Nf1 b6 25. Ne3 Bb7 26.
f3 (26. Nd5+ Kd6 27. Nxf6 $140 Rf8 28. Nd5 Rxf2 $17) 26... Rg8 27. Bd1 Kd6 28.
Rd2 Raf8 29. a4 f5 30. exf5 gxf5 31. f4 {Probably more stubborn is:} (31. g4
hxg4 32. fxg4 f4 33. Nf5+ Rxf5 34. gxf5 e4 $17 {[%csl Rd4,Rf5,Rh4][%cal Re4e3,
Rf4f3,Rd6e5]}) 31... Rxg3 32. Nc2 (32. fxe5+ Ke6 33. Rf2 f4 34. Bxh5 f3 35.
Bg4+ Kxe5 36. Nf5+ Kf4 $19) 32... Be4 33. fxe5+ Kxe5 34. Nxd4 cxd4 35. Bxh5 Rh8
36. Bf7 Rxh4 37. Kb2 Rhh3 38. c5 bxc5 39. a5 Ra3 40. a6 Ra4 41. Be8 c4 42. Rf2
Rb3+ {0-1 (42) Skembris,S (2560)-Van Wely,L (2560) Skei 1993 [Bojkov]}) 5...
O-O 6. Bg5 h6 7. Be3 e5 8. d5 c6 9. h4 $1 {The second Botvinnik's idea in
action.} cxd5 10. cxd5 Nbd7 11. h5 g5 $4 {[%csl Rg5,Rg7,Rh6] After this Black
is strategically lost. His kingside bishop is sealed, he lacks his usual
kingside play (in fact his right-wing might be attacked in the future) whereas
White can do anything he likes on the opposite flank.} 12. f3 a6 13. g4 {
[%csl Gd5,Rd6,Ge4,Re5,Gf3,Gg4,Rg5,Rg7,Gh5,Rh6]} b5 {A most welcomed move by
White. The more Black advances his queenside pawns, the easier it will be for
Petrosian to attack them and create weaknesses.} 14. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb5]} b4 15.
Nb1 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Ra4a5] Heading to the weakened c4 square.} a5
16. Nd2 Nc5 {Now comes Petrosian's pet manoeuvre.} 17. Bxc5 $1 {The most active
black piece is annihilated. On top of this, the d5 pawn becomes a defended
passer, whereas the c5 pawn- backward and weak.} dxc5 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gf6e8,
Ge8d6]} 18. Bb5 $3 {The key to the position. Petrosian prevents the cementing
manoeuvre Nf6-e8-d6. His ideal piece ration is a super white knight on c4
versus the black dark-squared bishop.} Bb7 19. Ne2 Ne8 20. Bxe8 $1 Rxe8 21. Nc4
{Black is busted, he can only trade one of the enemy knights for his good
bishop.} Ba6 22. Qb3 Qf6 23. Rc1 Bf8 24. Ng3 Bc8 25. O-O Rd8 26. Kg2 Ra7 27.
Rf2 Kh7 28. Rfc2 Qa6 29. Nxe5 Rc7 30. Nc4 Bg7 31. Qd3 Kg8 32. Rd2 Re7 33. e5
Bxe5 34. Nxe5 Rxe5 35. Qxa6 Bxa6 36. Rxc5 Bc8 37. Rxa5 f5 38. gxf5 Bxf5 39.
Nxf5 Rxf5 40. Rb5 Rdf8 41. d6 Rxb5 42. axb5 Kf7 43. d7 1-0

