{[%evp 0,114,27,22,63,63,73,70,71,38,38,38,42,26,22,23,39,28,40,37,27,16,16,7,
2,-16,-23,-19,-3,0,0,0,24,0,40,10,39,10,17,9,7,-1,14,16,24,0,17,19,24,17,16,4,
-3,24,18,41,48,48,48,48,44,44,43,43,43,43,43,38,38,44,31,44,58,71,77,105,93,86,
92,51,54,0,55,63,60,0,0,0,24,10,50,11,218,-59,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-22,-118,-140,
-285,-307,-275,-313,-413,-413,-428,-428,-428,-428,-436,-477]} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 g6
{The Modern defense. Nakamura does not mind repeating the successful opening
from Leuven.} 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. Bc4 {Anand deviates first.} Nf6 5. Qe2 O-O 6. O-O
Bg4 7. c3 Nc6 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e5 10. d5 ({Black did well in the opening
after:} 10. Rd1 Nd7 11. Be3 Qe7 12. Na3 Nb6 13. Bb5 f5 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. exf5
e4 16. f6 Rxf6 17. Qe2 Rf5 {in Bacrot,E (2718)-Ponomariov,R (2714) Beijing 2014
}) 10... Ne7 11. Bd3 Nd7 12. c4 f5 13. Qd1 $146 {This turns out to be a
novelty.} ({An email game saw:} 13. Nc3 fxe4 14. Qxe4 Nc5 15. Qe2 Nf5 {with
slight edge for White, Nightingale,D (2506)-Alonso Gonzalez,C (2497) ICCF
email 2009}) 13... c6 ({Another construction is:} 13... Nc5 14. Nc3 (14. Bc2)
14... a5 {which intends to slow White down on the queenside.}) 14. Nc3 cxd5 15.
cxd5 {From the Modern the players ended up in KID waters and Nakamura
performs now a typical manoeuvre.} Kh8 $1 {[%cal Gg8h8,Ge7g8,Gg7h6] A pure
positional idea. Black intends to trade his "bad" bishop.} 16. Be3 (16. a4 {
does not lead White anywhere after} Ng8 17. a5 a6) 16... Ng8 {The point behind
Black's previous move. Bg7-h6 comes next.} 17. Rc1 {Anand is playing on the
side where he is better.} ({Another way to play the position is:} 17. exf5 gxf5
18. f4 {[%csl Re5,Gf4,Rf5][%cal Gf2f4]}) ({t is not easy to prevent the trade} 
17. Qd2 $4 f4 {[%csl Re3] drops a piece.}) ({Whereas} 17. Qc1 f4 {[%csl Rg1]
[%cal Gf4f3] followed by f4-f3 looks annoying for White.}) 17... a6 {Excellent
prophylaxys.} ({The immediate} 17... Bh6 {would have allowed} 18. exf5 gxf5 19.
Bxh6 Nxh6 20. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Rd6,Ge6][%cal Rb5c7,Rc7e6] and White can easily
develop his queenside initiative after} Nc5 21. Bb1 a6 22. b4 $1) ({On the
other hand} 17... f4 18. Bd2 f3 19. g3 {does not achieve anything substantial
for Black.}) 18. Rc2 Bh6 19. Bxh6 Nxh6 {Black has achieved almost everything
that he wanted, but there are still dangers awaiting him on the queenside.} 20.
Qd2 f4 ({If} 20... Ng8 21. Rfc1 (21. b4) 21... Nc5 22. b4 {builds initiative
on the queenside for White.}) 21. Rfc1 Ng8 22. f3 (22. b4 {at once made sense
too, as White should not be worried of} f3 23. g3 {[%cal Gd3f1,Gf1h3]}) 22...
Ngf6 23. Nd1 a5 {Nakamura is correctly trying to seal the queenside.} ({
The immediate} 23... Nc5 {can be met with the interesting pawn sacrifice} 24.
b4 ({Or White can simply prepare the b2-b4 advance with} 24. Kh2) 24... Nxd3
25. Qxd3 Qb6+ 26. Nf2 Qxb4 27. Rc7) 24. Nf2 ({Also interesting was to keep the
knight where it was with} 24. b3 Nc5 25. Kh2 Qb6 {As it might be useful on the
queenside. For example:} 26. Nb2 $1 Nfd7 27. Nc4 Qc7 28. Na3 {intending
Bd3-b5! with advantage for White.}) 24... Nc5 {[%csl Gc5] Trying to lock the
rooks, but in vain.} 25. Bb5 {Cutting the support from the other knight.} ({
The immediate sacrifice was also interesting} 25. Rxc5 dxc5 26. Rxc5 {Now
Black has to be extremely careful. The generally desirable} Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6]
with the idea to block the d5 passer fails short to} ({Better is} 26... Nd7 {
although White also has compensation after} 27. Rc3 (27. Rb5 b6)) 27. Qc3 {
[%csl Re5]} Qd6 28. Ng4 {[%cal Rg4e5,Rc3e5,Ge4e5,Gd5d6] and White wins a
second pawn and the game.}) 25... Qb6 26. Rxc5 $1 {[%csl Rd6] Of course! In
locked pawn chains, it is always great to knock down the base pawn.} dxc5 27. a4
c4 $1 {[%cal Gb6g1] Nakamura also knows his stuff. Black needs open files for
his major pieces.} ({Passive defence will lead Black nowhere, say} 27... Rf7
28. Qc3) ({Or} 27... Rac8 28. Qc3 Qd6 29. Nd3 {and White enjoys large
advantage.}) 28. Qc3 $1 {Heading for the more important central pawn.} (28.
Rxc4 {would have allowed Black a chance to organize his defences after} Rfc8
29. Qc3 Rxc4 30. Qxc4 Ne8 31. Qc3 Qc7 {although White might still be better
here after} 32. Bc4 $5) 28... Qd6 ({Not} 28... Qd4 29. Qxd4 exd4 30. Rxc4) 29.
Qxc4 Rac8 $1 {[%csl Gc8] Another excellent defensive move. Normally the two
rooks are better than the queen, but in this particular case, the black queen
enjoys a lot of entry points and can easily torture the opponent's king.} ({
The other defences were perspectiveless, say} 29... Nh5 30. Qc7 Qxc7 31. Rxc7 {
[%csl Rh8][%cal Rc7h7,Rc7a7] with penetration on the seventh rank}) ({Or} 29...
Rf7 30. Nd3 {and White combines pressure in the centre with play along the
open c-file.}) 30. Qxc8 Rxc8 31. Rxc8+ Kg7 32. Nd3 ({Or} 32. Kh2 Nh5) 32... Nh5
33. Kf1 $1 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gg1f1] Anand understood that his king has no
future on the kingside.} Qb6 34. Nc5 Kh6 $1 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Gh6g5,Gg5h4,Gh4g3]
And this is one of the reasons why. The black king will be safer in front of
his own pawn chain and will actually attack the enemy pawns.} 35. Ke1 Ng3 {
This costs Black two tempos.} ({The immediate} 35... Kg5 $1 {[%csl Rg2][%cal
Rg5h4,Rh4g3,Rg3g2] was better, when the only one to play for the win would be
the second player. Here is a sample line-} 36. Kd1 Kh4 37. Kc2 Kg3 38. Nd7 Qd6
39. Nc5 Kxg2 40. Nxb7 Qb6 41. Nc5 Kxf3) 36. Kd1 $1 Kh5 37. Kc2 Kh4 38. Kb1 ({
White could (should?) have used the delay on the kingside with} 38. Nb3 $1 Nh5
({Not} 38... Qf2+ $2 39. Kb1 Qxg2 $2 40. d6) 39. Kb1 Kg3 40. Rc2 $1 {Next the
rook will be placed behind the passer, on the optimal square, both defending and
attacking. And if White forces the black queen onto the defence he should be
better.}) 38... Nh5 39. Ka2 Kg3 {[%csl Rf3,Rg2,Gg3,Rh3]} 40. Nd3 {The game
enters the time-trouble zone when a queen is a great asset.} Qd4 ({But not} 
40... Kxg2 41. Nxe5 {when the white pawns will soon become unstoppable.}) 41.
Rc2 Nf6 42. Nc5 ({Or} 42. Nc1 Qb4) 42... Qd1 43. Kb3 g5 44. Nd3 Nd7 {The human
decision, but that lets the d-passer running.} ({The computer claims
positional draw after} 44... h5 45. Nxe5 Nxd5 46. exd5 Qxd5+ 47. Nc4 Qd3+ 48.
Rc3 Qd1+ (48... Qd5 $5) 49. Rc2 ({As it is too risky for White to deviate from
the perpetual with} 49. Ka2 Kxg2 50. Nxa5 Qd5+ 51. Ka3 Kxh3 {the kingside
passers become too strong.})) 45. Kc3 ({Anand should have seized his chance-} 
45. d6 $1 {would have helped White to play for a win. Nothing is certain after
this study-like continuation though} h5 46. Kc3 Qg1 47. Rf2 Nc5 48. d7 Nxd3 49.
Bxd3 Qxf2 50. d8=Q Qc5+ 51. Kd2 Qf2+ {Maybe our readers can help us with final
verdict?}) ({White should however avoid} 45. Bxd7 $2 Qxd3+ 46. Rc3 Qd4 {
[%cal Gd4b4,Rg3g2]}) 45... Nb6 46. Nxe5 $2 {A huge step in the wrong direction.
} ({It was not too late for} 46. d6 $1 Qg1 47. Rf2 {cutting the queen away
when White might be simply winning.}) 46... Qe1+ ({Perhaps Anand expected} 
46... Nxd5+ 47. exd5 Qe1+ 48. Rd2 ({Or} 48. Kd4 Qe3+ 49. Kc4 Qxe5) 48... Qxe5+
49. Kc2 Qd6 {but with the passive queen Black can never play for a win.}) 47.
Kb3 $6 {Another inaccuracy.} ({Correct was} 47. Rd2 Nxd5+ 48. exd5 Qxe5+ 49.
Kc2 {when the draw should be the most likely outcome.}) 47... Qb4+ $1 {Now
Nakamura breaks open the white king.} 48. Ka2 Nxa4 49. Bxa4 Qxa4+ 50. Kb1 Qd4
51. Nc4 a4 $3 {And finds the amazing win!} ({A move like} 51... h5 {would have
led to a draw after} 52. Rd2 $3 Qxc4 53. d6 Qf1+ 54. Ka2 Qc4+ 55. Kb1) 52. d6 (
{Here} 52. Rd2 {does not save White due to} Qxc4 53. d6 a3 $1 {and the opened
white king allows Black a chance to play either for checkmate, or to grab some
pawns. For example:} 54. bxa3 Qb3+ 55. Kc1 Qc3+ 56. Kd1 Qa1+ 57. Ke2 (57. Kc2
Qa2+ 58. Kd1 ({The exposed nature of the white king is revealed also in the
line:} 58. Kc1 Qxa3+ 59. Kc2 Qa4+ 60. Kc1 Qc6+ 61. Kd1 Qd7 62. e5 Qa4+ 63. Kc1
Qa1+ 64. Kc2 Qxe5 65. d7 Qc7+ 66. Kd1 Qd8) 58... Qb1+ 59. Ke2 Kxg2 {and Black
wins.}) 57... Kxg2 58. d7 Qf1# $1) 52... Qd1+ 53. Rc1 Qd3+ 54. Rc2 b5 {Now it
is curtains.} 55. Nd2 ({Or} 55. Ne5 Qd1+ 56. Rc1 Qxd6) 55... b4 ({There was
nothing wrong with} 55... Qxd6 {and wins.}) 56. Kc1 b3 (56... Qe2 {was strong
too.}) 57. Rc3 Qxd6 0-1

