d6 5. Bd3 O-O 6. Nge2 c6 7. O-O a6 8. h3 b5 9. b3 Nbd7 10. Be3 e5 11. d5 cxd5
12. cxd5 {The most aggressive way for Black to advance the f-pawn is connected
with the manoeuvre :} Nh5 {[%cal Gf7f5] In this case the knight is getting ready
to occupy the wonderful f4 spot once that the f-file is opened. However, there
might be a certain drawback related to the idea, especially when the white
knight is on e2.} ({nstead of the obvious move in the game my student Charles
Sonido chose to insert the move:} 12... Nc5 {First and only after:} 13. Bc2 Nh5
({Charles know the Petrosian-Schweber game that we have already discussed and
is aware that:} 13... b4 {Can be met with the blockading:} 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15.
Na4 {[%cal Ga4b2,Gb2c4,Gf6e8,Ge8d6] White will sooner or later bring his
knight to the fabulous outpost on c4. True, Black's prospects are not as grim
as in the game of the world champion and he can figth on with:} Qc7 16. Rc1 {
[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc1c5,Gg7h6]} ({Notice the natural desire of the black bishop
to enter the game:} 16. Bd3 {[%cal Ga1c1]} Bd7 17. Nb2 $2 Nxd5 $1 {[%csl Gb2]
[%cal Ge5e4,Gg7b2]}) ({The natural:} 16. Nb2 {can be met with:} Ne8 17. Nc4 a5
({Or:} 17... Nd6 18. Nxd6 Qxd6 19. Bd3 {[%csl Gh6,Gg5][%cal Gg6g5,Gh7h6] and
we see the difference between this game and the Petrosian-Schweber one
clearly- the black bishop is not blocked by his own pawns (they were on g5 and
h6 in the game), whereas the white knight is far away from the c4 spot yet.})
18. Bd3 Ba6 19. Nb2 {[%cal Ga1c1] White looks better here, but Black can play
on.})) {Now White committed a typical mistake:} 14. g4 $2 {[%csl Rf4][%cal
Rh5f4] That only poured oil in Black's kingside fire.} Nf4 $1 {[%cal Rh8a1]
The knight did not mean to retreat for sure!} ({Even:} 14... Qh4 15. gxh5 Bxh3
16. Re1 (16. Ng3 Bxf1 17. Qxf1 f5) 16... Bg4 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gg4f3,Gh4h3]
with strong attack looked appealing for Black.}) 15. Nxf4 exf4 16. Bd4 Qh4 {
The dark squares around the first player's monarch are inviting the enemy
pieces to launch a decisive attack. Black won a nice game after:} ({But actually,
an instant win would have been:} 16... Bxd4 $1 17. Qxd4 Qh4 {[%csl Rg4,Rh3]}
18. Kg2 Bxg4 $1 19. hxg4 Qxg4+ 20. Kh2 f3 21. Rg1 Qh4#) 17. Bxg7 Qxh3 18. f3
Qg3+ 19. Kh1 Kxg7 20. Qd4+ f6 21. Qf2 Qh3+ 22. Qh2 Qxh2+ (22... Bxg4) 23. Kxh2
h5 24. gxh5 Rh8 25. Rh1 Rxh5+ 26. Kg1 Rxh1+ 27. Kxh1 Bd7 28. Ne2 g5 29. Kg2 Rh8
30. Nd4 (30. Rh1 Rxh1 31. Kxh1 b4 {[%csl Gb4,Ya2,Yb3][%cal Ba6a5,Bd7b5]}) 30...
Rh3 31. b4 Rg3+ 32. Kf2 Bh3 33. Rh1 (33. bxc5 Rg2+ 34. Ke1 Rg1+ (34... Rxc2)
35. Kd2 Rxa1 36. cxd6 (36. c6)) 33... Nd7 34. Bd3 Ne5 35. Bf1 Bd7 36. a3 g4 37.
Be2 gxf3 38. Nxf3 Ng4+ 39. Ke1 Ne3 40. Kd2 Bg4 (40... f5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4]})
41. Nd4 Rg2 42. Kd3 (42. Ne6+ $1 Bxe6 43. dxe6 {[%csl Gf4]} f3 {[%csl Ge6]} 44.
Kxe3 fxe2 45. e7 (45. Rc1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gc1c6]}) (45. Re1 Kf8 46. Rxe2 (46.
Kf3 Rg7 47. Rxe2 Rc7 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Gc7c3,Gc3a3,Gf8e7,Ge7e6,Gf3f4,Gf4f5]})
46... Rxe2+ 47. Kxe2 Ke7 48. Ke3 Kxe6) 45... Kf7) 42... Nc4 43. Bxg4 Rxg4 44.
Nf5+ Kg6 45. a4 f3 (45... Ne5+ {[%csl Ga4][%cal Gb5a4]}) 46. axb5 axb5 47. Ne3
Ne5+ 48. Kd4 Rf4 (48... Rg2 $1 {[%cal Gg2d2,Gd2d3,Gd3e3]}) 49. Rf1 f2 50. Nd1 (
50. Ng2 {[%csl Gf4,Gf2][%cal Gg2h4]}) 50... Ng4 51. Kd3 Kg5 52. Kd2 Kh4 53. Ne3
Kg3 54. Rh1 Nxe3 55. Kxe3 f1=Q {0-1 White resigns. 0-1 (55) tonythetiger11 
(2193)-chessmonger808 (2164) lichess.org 2020}) 13. Rc1 f5 14. exf5 gxf5 {
Black did everything he wanted, however now comes:} 15. Ng3 $3 {[%csl Rf5,Rh5]
[%cal Rg3f5] The pressure against the f5 pawn forces Black to swap the knights
off.} ({If hite did not have this resource, he should have switched to
Botvinnik's Idea 1 with:} 15. f4 e4 16. Bb1 {[%csl Gc3,Rc6,Rc8,Gd4,Ge2,Re3,Re6,
Rf5][%cal Ge3d4,Gd1d2,Gc3d1,Gd1e3,Ye2d4,Yg2g4]} Qe7 17. Bd4 (17. Qd2 {[%cal
Gg2g4]}) {Things will be unclear after:} 17... Rf7 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8g6]} 18. Qd2
Nf8 19. Bxg7 (19. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1e3]}) 19... Rxg7 20. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1e3]} Ng6 {
[%cal Gg6h4,Gh5f4]}) 15... Nxg3 16. fxg3 {[%csl Rf5,Gg2,Gg3,Gh3][%cal Rd3f5,
Rf1f5] The consequences of the trade strongly favor White: 1) He traded an
important attacking piece by Black. 2) The white kingside has been reinforced.
The doubled pawns are extremely good defenders of the king. 3) Last, but not
least- the f-file has been opened for the white rooks and the f5 pawn is no
longer an attacking asset but a defensive liability. White's plan is simple
and unstoppable- force e5-e4 to make the f5 pawn even weaker (backward pawn),
double the rooks on the f-file, transfer the knight to d4. This should be
enough to force the collapse of the black pawn chain. And if it is not- then
he can always use the g3-g4 advance to finish his plan.} Nc5 (16... e4 {
[%csl Re4,Rf5][%cal Bg3g4]} 17. Bb1 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gc3e2,Ge2d4,Gd4e6,Gd4c6,Re2f4,
Rf4e6,Rg3g4]}) 17. Bb1 b4 18. Ne2 Bd7 19. Rf2 {[%csl Rf5,Gg2,Gg3,Gh3]} Rc8 20.
Qd2 a5 21. Rcf1 {[%csl Rf5]} Ne4 (21... e4 22. Nd4 {[%csl Rf5]}) 22. Bxe4 fxe4
{[%csl Re4,Re5,Gg2,Gg3]} 23. Rxf8+ Bxf8 24. Bh6 Qb6+ 25. Kh2 Be7 26. g4 Qc5 27.
Ng3 Qc2 28. Qe3 Rc3 29. Qg5+ {Sturua, Zurab - Ghinda, Mihail Viorel, 1-0,
Katerini GP, 1993} 1-0

