little, mainly because White cannot use the open c-file.} 30. Qf2 (30. Rf1 Bg5
31. Qc5 {looks more active to me. The idea is to exchange the queens in
appropriate moment.}) 30... Bg5 31. Rf1 Rf8 32. Nc4 Nxc4 33. Rxc4 h5 {[%cal
Rh5h4,Rg5f4,Rd8g5] Black intends to further expand on the kingside, his
advantage is indisputable.} 34. g3 {Aimed against black's idea-h5-h4, Bg5-f4,
Qd8-g5.} h4 $36 {>>} 35. Be2 Ra8 36. Bg4 Kg7 37. Kg2 Qe7 {/\ Ra3, Rh8} 38. Qc5
Ra2+ 39. Rf2 Rxf2+ 40. Kxf2 (40. Qxf2 {>=}) 40... Qf6+ 41. Kg2 Rh8 42. Rc2 (42.
Qf2 h3+ 43. Kg1 Qa6 $17) 42... hxg3 43. hxg3 Bf4 $1 $17 44. Qf2 (44. gxf4 Qxf4
$19) 44... Qg5 45. Qf3 (45. gxf4 Qxg4+ 46. Qg3 Qd1 $19) 45... Qh6 $1 46. Kf1
Bxg3 $1 47. Rc7 (47. Qxg3 Qh1+ 48. Ke2 Qxe4+ $19) 47... Bf4 48. Be6 Rf8 49. d6
Qh4 50. d7 Rd8 51. Bh3 Ra8 $19 52. Ke2 $138 Ra2+ 53. Kd3 Qf6 54. Kc4 Qa6+ {
0-1 Mohr,S-Miles,A/Bad Worishofen 1990/Inf 49/[Miles,A] (54) Mate is
inevitable.} (54... Qa6+ 55. Kd5 Rd2+ 56. Kc5 Rc2+ 57. Kd5 Qb5+ 58. Kd6 Qxb4+
59. Kd5 Qd4#)) 14... Bg7 15. b4 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gc4c5]} c5 {[%csl Rb4,Rc4,Gc5]
Same move, forced as the game above.} 16. Nb5 Bd7 17. Rab1 cxb4 18. axb4 Bxb5
19. cxb5 Nc7 {[%cal Gc7e8,Ge8d6] Same maneuver. The knight is ideal on the d6
outpost.} 20. Qe3 Ne8 21. Nd2 Nd6 22. Ra1 Bf6 {[%cal Gf6g5] Even this manoeuvre
is the same, including the little tactics. Lucky preparation, which however
proves again why it is so important not only to memorize the opening moves
but to investigate what should follow afterwards.} 23. Qd3 (23. Qxh6 $4 Bg5 {
[%csl Rd2,Rh6][%cal Rg5d2,Rg5h6]}) 23... h5 24. Ra2 ({Or:} 24. b6 axb6 25. Rxa8
Rxa8 26. Qf3 Bg5 27. Nc4 Nxc4 28. Bxc4 Rf8 $15 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gh5h4,Gg5f4,
Gg8g7,Re7b4]}) 24... Rdc8 25. Qf3 Bg5 26. Nb3 Qc7 27. Bd3 Qc3 28. Nc5 {Now
black needs to reinforce the position of his rooks.} Rf8 {But not the
premature:} (28... b6 $2 29. Nb7 Nxb7 30. Qxf7+ Kh8 31. Qxg6 Be3+ 32. Kh1 Qxd3
33. Qxh5+ {Where white has at least perpetual.} Kg8 34. Qg4+ Kh8 35. Qh3+ Kg8 {
Or a win...} 36. Raf2 $1 Qxe4 37. Qe6+ Kh8 38. Rf3 Qxf3 39. Qxe5+ Kg8 40. Qe6+
Kh8 41. gxf3 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Re3,Rh8]}) 29. Nd7 (29. Kh1 Qxb4 30. Nd7 Rfe8 31.
Nf6+ Bxf6 32. Qxf6 {and the computer claims enough compensation here.}) 29...
Rfd8 30. Nc5 Rab8 {[%cal Rb7b6] Now b7-b6 is a threat.} 31. Rxa7 Qxb4 {[%csl
Rc5][%cal Rg1a7,Ra7g1]} 32. Qf2 Qc3 {[%cal Rd6b5,Rg5e3] Black threatens Nb5.}
33. Ra2 (33. Kh1 b6 34. Qg3 Bf4 35. Na4 Qd4 36. Qf3 Ra8 {[%csl Ra4] white is
hopeless.}) 33... b6 34. Rc2 Qa3 35. Ne6 $1 {The last chance in the arising
time-trouble.} fxe6 36. Qg3 Nxe4 {The simplest, though the silicon friend
finds win after:} (36... Rd7 37. Qxg5 $6 (37. Rd1 $5 {makes the things quite
complicated.} Bf4 38. Qxg6+ Rg7 39. Qxe6+ Kh8 $17) 37... Qxd3 38. Qxg6+ (38.
